@NODE "Mail_0" "Yet More DLL...."
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 1 Apr 1999 02:40:20 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Yet More DLL....
Date: Thu, 1 Apr 1999 02:41:47 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi again,

 Well I`ve had a change of heart...seeing as a few people have taken an
interest I`m going to work on it for another day (though I`m getting sick of
the sight of linked lists..lol). I have fixed a couple of bugs...but I think
I`m going to rewrite some of it (ie change the lists) for a couple of
reasons....and I think I can make it look like a blitz list to blitz. All it
will mean is a bit more setting up before you use the list....and you will
have to have 2 variables, a list head, and a list node (ie, current item
pointer). This does have an advantage....the way I did my list`s was to
cheat, and have a node at the top of them, with a head pointer..so I could
always reach the head of the list from anywhere inside the list. This meant
that each item took 18 bytes without any extra data, as I wanted to try and
implement gtlistview compatibility. (ie, I had to leave a word pad gap and a
string gap).....which takes away a lot of memory when your list reaches
100,000. The new way it would work is (this will only make sense to people
who have seen the other version)

deftype .dllhead *myhead                ;this is the list head..still a
pointer needed
deftype .myitem *mylist                     ;this would be the `current
item` in the list

then you`d call

*myhead=INIT_LIST{&*mylist,sizeof .myitem} (note the &* start for the
current item pointer)

if *myhead=0 then end         ;couldn`t initilize list

and from then on, you`d put *myhead in the routine calls (just *, not &*)
and access the item in the list as normal by using *mylist

ie...

if ADD_ITEM{*myhead}

 *mylist\name="fred"

endif


does this make sense to anyone?? It makes it a lil more confusing, but each
item only requires an overhead of 8 bytes (a lot better than 18 bytes per
item) and *SHOULD* allow you full gtlistview compatibility (ie, you make
your item

newtype .myitem
 node.dll
 pad.w
 string.s
end newtype

just like you would with a blitz list...and then hopefully, you can use it
in your gtlistview call...

If I manage this..I`ll post it to the list if that`s okay....and after that
if any more bugs are detected I`d put it updates on a site, or aminet :).

Dave


P.s. anyone think of a better short name instead of dll???



