@NODE "Mail_32" "What's Fun?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 27 Mar 1999 06:30:22 +0000
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 27 Mar 1999 00:26:07 +0500
Subject: What's Fun?
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 27-Mar-99, Mikkel L=F8kke flashed:

>Well how many times is that fun ? And while strapping C4 explosives to a=

>persons back might be fun to watch, I'm sure the explosion would set off=
 some
>alarm resulting in your swift execution. It would in Mission: Impossible=
 or
>GoldenEye. Also a short game isn't fun, I personally would be rather pis=
sed
if
>I'd paid some =A330 for a game I could complete in a matter of hours....=
 (Which
>is why I adore Baldur's Gate)

  Personally, I'm just the opposite.  I HATE games that try to force me t=
o
play for days.  And I tend to want to murder the programmers of them for
being so arrogant and self-consumed as to try to force their will on me.
Such games soon lose any attraction for me unless I can find a way to
shortcut it or cheat.  It's like taking hours to tell a joke.  Nobody
cares by the time you finally spew out the punch line.  The only
exception is strategy games.  Even then I prefer to be able to do my own
thing instead of being limited by some programmers ego and lack of
imagination.  That is why puzzel games usually bore me to death.
  By far the best and most fun puzzel "game" I have played is trying to
create some decent software.  Now THAT's a fun "game".  But you have to
take a break from it every so often or it'll drive you crazy.

  I am trying to creat some games for working stiffs like me, because all=

the games seem to be created for the reviewers and the game junkies who
seem to have nothing else to do with their lives and no need to earn a
living.  My personal opinion is that most of the loud-mouthed people who
always complain about games being to hard or short are those who steal
them.  (Not saying that applys to you of course, but one gets the
impression that most of the loud-mouths on the AmigaNutta list for
instance are pirates and/or not supporting themselves (ie little kids).
  I want to create some games which really have a real-life feel in
allowing the player to choose his own course of action.  It is high time
for games to conform themselves to the user instead of the other way arou=
nd.
Such a game could be SO much more interesting (but of course would force =
us
programmers to get off our lazy duffs and WORK!).  Myst was a huge game f=
or
its time, but still a rigid puzzel without any soal or life.  Multi-
threading is not enough, there need to be enough real possibilities in a
large enouth world or universe to make it feel "real".  Some of you may
know the guys in World Foundry doing Explorer2260 and the related univers=
e.
I think they are on the right track.  Especially by makeing a number of
loosely related games based in the same world or universe the sum of the
whole definately become much greater than the individual parts, and it al=
l
starts taking on a reality which any one by itself lacks.  Within the gam=
es
this is true of the sceanerios and game-play threads as well.  And if a
game must be limited in size, then it should concentrate on one particula=
r
theme with a wealth of detail which makes it feel like part of a larger
whole even if it's designed for a quick recreational splurge.
  Games appeal to different people for different reasons but tend to fall=

into two classes:  those attempting to keep the emotions on edge and the
adrenlin flowing, and those attempting to stimulate reasoning and
imagionation.  A game which can successfully bridge the gap and have a
well-balanced element of both types can sometimes become greater than
either by itself.  Whether it appeals on both counts or repels on both
counts and to what classes of people is up to the planners and programmer=
s
to figure out and to accomplish.  But one thing it would behoove us all t=
o
remember, that we must choose between deciding on the target audience(s)
and attempting to give them what THEY want so we can make money, or
pleasing ourselves in the belief that there will be others with the same
taste to buy our products, or just pleasing ourselves entirely and not
caring about the market.
  I am going by the second line of thinking, but ready to veer to the
third the instant the second doesn't pan out.  ;)  In other words, when I=

work on applications I try to make them usefull to others, but when
it comes to games, I just wanna have fun (even when programming them).

  I guess I'm just not cut out for the commercial market bit with games,
either as a user or as a programmer.


cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



