@NODE "Mail_83" "Re: Version $"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 13:14:52 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 1999 07:08:25 -0500
Subject: Re: Version $

Hi amorel

On 22-Mar-99, amorel wrote:
> What code do you need to put in to be able to use your prog with version?
> 
> I do this:
> 
> goto skipthis
> even
>   dc.b "VER$: blah blah"
> even
> .skipthis:
> 
> This at least makes the info appear in a text viewer, if it reads in exe
> files. Without the goto it crashes miserably :-)

The CLI Version command is very picky - it looks for the keyword "$VER:" in
the file.  It must also be in the exactly correct format.

This also goes for the VersionWB program, and anything else that looks for a
version number (like an installer script)

Here is an example:

v$="$VER: Crazy8 v2.9a (14-02-99) by Curt Esser"
     ^      ^      ^        ^         ^
     |      |      |        |         |
     |      |      |        |     Other stuff
     |      |      |  Date must have "()" around, and this exact format
     |      |    Version must have "v" and version with no spaces
     |   Program's name
   Keyword must be exactly this way -  "VER$:" won't work!

You can use this with the dcb method, or just as a string like I show.  It
will work either way.

There shouldn't be a problem unless something else in your exec has it's own
"$VER: " string.  That is why Blitz libraries have no version strings in
them.
If you find one that does, do the same as below, then re-make your deflibs.

If there is something else in your exec with a "$VER:" just find it with a
hex editor and change it to "XVER:" or anything else so the version command
will ignore it.

            
              
    

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
