 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 10 Mar 1999 17:29:54 +0000
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 13:39:52 +0300
Subject: Re: Update of what is going on with installing blitz 2.1
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 09-Mar-99, Mikkel L=F8kke wrote.

>  Hello Sami.
>  =

>  On 09-Mar-99, Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen wrote:
>  =

>  >>  > Alas I made it log to a revocerable ram disc - alas it either
didn't survive
>  >>  > or wasn't there after the reset.  :(
>  >>  You mean RAD: ? RAD: Will survive anything but a Hardreset (Such a=
s
>  > switching the power off).
>  =

>  > Well you forget to mention that memory sanity check is another one,
which
>  > will flush any resetproof memory areas.
>  =

>  No, I didn't forget, I wasn't aware of it.
>  =

>  > So if program have somehow messed with memory pool (freed memory twi=
ce
or
>  > freed memory with invalid pointer) you can bet that there will NOT B=
E
ANY
>  > RADs left after reset!
>  =

>  Not even if you protect it with an MMU ?

Well If memory sanity check fails EXEC will reinit the memory pools from
scratch and you can't prevent that.
This memory freeing thing is the most commond problem because programmers=

does not keep good record of their allocated memory etc. and if you
accidentaly free memory that is already freed or you are trying to free
memory like this.

Mymem.l=3DAllocMem(Size.l,Options.l)
freeMem(MyMem+40,size-40)
freemem(Mymem,40)

So you should always free the memory in same sized chunks as you allocate=
d
it or you will trash the EXEC memory pool. And RESET follows...

-- =


            Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen   A1260 50MB 4.5GB 2X 56k HP LaserJet4L
            EMail: sami.naatanen@dlc.fi




