@NODE "Mail_98" "Re: Unsigned Bytes"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 22:04:13 +0000
          Paris Mon, 1 Mar 1999 23:00:16 +0100 (MET)
From: Mathias PARNAUDEAU <mathias.p@wanadoo.fr>
Date: Mon, 01 Mar 1999 22:20:12 +0100
Subject: Re: Unsigned Bytes
Encoding: quoted-printable

Le 01-Mars-99, Mikkel L=F8kke a =E9crit:


>> I know this is an array of 255 entries with each r,g and b entry being=

>> unsigned bytes, 0 to 255.

>Yes, so what's the problem ? Just read them as signed bytes and put them=
 in a
>palette. I think it should work. If you've allready tied this though (An=
d it
>didn't work) you can just convert them using this very simple formula :

>If signed.b < 0
>    unsigned value (should be stored in a word if using blitz) =3D
>256-abs(signed.b)
>end if :o>

Hi all,

I know Daniel found out his problem with unsigned bytes. When I need to p=
ut an
unsigned byte (in a palette register for example) I do that :

red.w=3Dpeek.b(adr)&ff                  ; reads a colour component
green.w=3Dpeek.b(adr+1)&ff
blue.w=3Dpeek.b(adr+2)&ff

agapalrgb palettenb,colournb,red.w,green.w,blue.w

You have to mask the numbers : Blitz thinks red, green, blue are positive=

numbers.

I would say firstly abs() is VERY slow, you should use
   if value<0
   then value=3D(NOT value)+1
instead of
   if value<0
   then value=3Dabs(value)

Bye,

                                 Mathias



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_99" "Re: Unsigned Bytes"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 23:24:56 +0000
 (envelope-from flameduck@software.dk)
 (envelope-from flameduck@software.dk)
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Tue, 02 Mar 1999 00:11:06 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: Unsigned Bytes
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Mathias.

On 01-Mar-99, Mathias PARNAUDEAU wrote:

> I would say firstly abs() is VERY slow, you should use
>   if value<0
>   then value=3D(NOT value)+1
> instead of
>   if value<0
>   then value=3Dabs(value)

Firstly abs is fast enough for converting 768 bytes in an area where spee=
d isn't critical (and setting up a palette is hardly very CPU intensive),=
 and second I was only displaying the maths behind it, not the fastest wa=
y to do it. You could even go "one step beyond" and just do it in assembl=
y (get the address of the palette, find out where the colour info starts,=
 and start moving the data, since in assembly signed or unsigned numbers =
depend on how YOU interpret them. $ff could be either 255 or -1, the CPU =
really doesn't care.)


Regards
-- =

