@NODE "Mail_104" "Re: UDP_Chat V2.3 on aminet"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 1 Apr 1999 02:49:58 +0100
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Thu, 01 Apr 1999 13:45:42 +1200
Subject: Re: UDP_Chat V2.3 on aminet

On 01-Apr-99, Chris Deeney wrote:
> ello Anton
> 
> On 30-Mar-99, Anton Reinauer wrote:
>> Yep, it that time again- V2.3 of my UDP_Chat is on Aminet
>> (dev/basic). I won't list all the improvements, as I did it the other
>> week.
>> 
>> For those that don't know they're a set of routines to put a
>> multi-player internet connection into a game, with full
>> connection/disconnection routines.
  
> Ahhhh good! i like the way it tells u when another person disconnects
> or when the server goes down, kewl.

  Yeah :)  - do you know how much work went into getting the
connect/disconnect routines working properly- arrggg- that's been the
hardest thing yet! 
  It also needs an extra status- 'Waiting for Connection', so you can
put in a timeout routine, and maybe a keepalive system like Quake has,
in case it takes awhile to get the connection fully up and running, or
you have to load lots of GFX of the HDD, or swap Skins with the Server
etc.

> Maybe u could make a seperate version without the terminal and the
> print commands etc.. like just give the user a send function and a
> recieve function and a status variable or something, so the coder
> could more or less implement the udp code straight away without
> having to remove the gui and all the print commands and stuff.
 
  Yes, I'm doing that in the next version :) This version is halfway
there already, as I took most things out of the main loop. 
  I'll take anything non-UPD related out of Comms_Housekeeping{} like
the Rexx stuff, and it will return different values if a user has
connected, or disconnected etc. All security messages will now be
stored in a string array, so they can be printed out by the user any
time (and way) they want. 
  I'll also change the way game data packets are delt with- they'll just
get thrown into a buffer and the user can deal with them as they wish,
also the player at your machine's, data will be put into that buffer and
delt with the same as the other player's (ie: the single-player data
will be handled the same as the multi-player). This way we can put an
artificial lag into the player's movements when using Peer-To-Peer, to
prevent there being too much of a discrepancy in a player's position on
different machines if you have higher lags.
   You could put in a lag of say half the current lag to the Server (to
be completely accurate), but you could probably take off another 
50-100 ms to improve playability. The more you took off the less fair it
would be to the other players; but with small lag times, it wouldn't
matter, and you could have the player move without any lag!!! This
system would also work with Client-Server if the Server didn't have a
analogue modem. This cuts down the lag from a standard Client-Server
system, by more than half!! -Am I brilliant, or am I brilliant!! :-))
   All the other calls to Print_String{} will be only be done if
#DEBUG=1, so with it off, all my routines will be GUI independant, and
Print_String could always be changed to outputting to a logfile to ram:
. UDP_Chat was always meant to be just a debugging interface, but it
took me awhile to tidy it up, as I'd never done anything like this (or
on this scale) before! :-)  

  Seeya- Anton

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      A500,DF1:,0.5MC,8.5MF,60HDD,WB3.1 &1.3/2.0 
    A1200,2M,CD-Rom,25/040,200/PPC ,WB3.0 
          
    Project: UDP_Chat [99%]- an Internet multi-player code, test-bed 
      for my game Pyro-Mid. - Aminet: dev/basic/UDP_Chat.lha (V2.1)
         <http://www.ww.co.nz/home/anton/>


