@NODE "Mail_106" "Re: Two mice?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 9 Mar 1999 18:17:23 +0000
 (envelope-from flameduck@software.dk)
 (envelope-from flameduck@software.dk)
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Tue, 09 Mar 1999 18:00:20 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: Two mice?
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Stephen.

On 08-Mar-99, Stephen Lebed wrote:

> Does anyone know if its possible to read mouse from each port?  I'm
> currently using SCREENMOUSE to read the normal mouse port, but I'd like=
> read a mouse on the joystick port as well.

Alex Moon once did a rather nice routine for this, it's included in it's =
full length below.

------- Begin 2nd Mouse Example -------

NEWTYPE .Dat
  Reg.l:  X.w:  Y.w:  cx.w:  cy.w
  MinX.w: MinY.w: MaxX.w: MaxY.w
End NEWTYPE
Dim M.Dat(1)
M.Dat(0)Reg=3D$dff00a ;Hardware reg for port 1 (mouse)
M.Dat(1)Reg=3D$dff00c ;Hardware reg for port 2 (joy)
M.Dat(0)MaxX=3D319;  Set max x boundary to 319
M.Dat(0)MaxY=3D255;  Set max y boundary to 255
M.Dat(1)MaxX=3D319;  Set max x boundary to 319
M.Dat(1)MaxY=3D255;  Set max y boundary to 255

Statement ReadMouse{Port}
  SHARED M.Dat()

  USEPATH M.Dat(Port)
  ocx.w=3Dcx
  ocy.w=3Dcy

  ; This is where the reading from the hardware regs is done
  cx=3DPeek.b(Reg+1)
  cy=3DPeek.b(Reg)

  ; Here the deltas are calculated
  dx.w=3Dcx-ocx: dy.w=3Dcy-ocy

  ; Wrap around counters
  If(dx<-127)  dx+256
  If(dx>127)   dx-256
  If(dy<-127)  dy+256
  If(dy>127)   dy-256

  ;Update coords
  X+dx:  Y+dy

  ;Don't you go beyond your limits
  If(X>MaxX)  X=3DMaxX
  If(X<MinX)  X=3DMinX
  If(Y>MaxY)  Y=3DMaxY
  If(Y<MinY)  Y=3DMinY
End Statement

BLITZ
Slice 0,44,2
BitMap 0,320,256,2
Cls 0
Line 0,0,5,5,1
GetaShape 0,0,0,6,6
GetaSprite 0,0
Cls 0
Show 0


BitMapOutput 0
; This is the loop you'd need
Repeat
  ReadMouse{0}
  ReadMouse{1}
  ShowSprite 0,M.Dat(0)X,M.Dat(0)Y,0
  ShowSprite 0,M.Dat(1)X,M.Dat(1)Y,2
  VWait
Until Joyb(0)
End

------- End 2nd Mouse example -------

As you can see it's an old ugly blitzmode thingy, but the technique is so=
lid, and should work on a system friendly intuition screen aswell.


Regards
