@NODE "Mail_129" "Re: This is getting annoying!! :(( (MEM LEAK, BAD CODING!)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 3 Mar 1999 14:35:26 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 3 Mar 1999 14:34:07 +0000
Date: Wed, 03 Mar 1999 14:12:44 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: This is getting annoying!! :(( (MEM LEAK, BAD CODING!)
Encoding: quoted-printable

Mikkel L=F8kke wrote:
> Hello Loki.
>
> > Intuition codeing is SLOW!.. how do you double buffer an
> > ituition screen?
> =

> another is creating a double height screen, and switching between
> the top half, and the bottom half. (This is what Paul Bukey does
> [or at least used to do], how do I know ? I have a screen promoter
> that forces autoscroll, and it wreaks havoc on foundation :o>)

I don`t use this any more. It was and still is a popular method
of double buffering on graphics cards. I now discovered that
allocating a bitmap and cludging a rastport to point to it is
a good way to do hidden rendering on graphics cards. I also realized
that double buffering isn`t very important on gfx cards anyway. The
latest version of Foundation has the double buffering disabled
and very few people noticed :) Of course, I'm not rendering pixels
and shapes to the display directly. All that is done in a chunky
buffer but then the chunky buffer is copied to the display while
it's actualy in view. It would look very nasty on a planar display
but looks okay in chunky.
 =

> > This was a demo style program I was working on, and required
> > all the speed it could grab!
> =

> Well, so now you have a program that is very fast, instead no-one
> can use it.... Hrmm...

Modern demos will probably use chunky graphics because thats the
only way to you do all the modern effects in the most efficient
way on faster cpu's. This means dual AGA (c2p) and cybergfx support
can be very easy to impliment. Planar modes usually point to
copper effects and blitter objects. I've not seen a demo like that
for a while.

Cheers,

Paul

-- =

< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >




@ENDNODE
