Hi Sami

On 02-Mar-99, Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen wrote:
> =

> Well I think I have revealed the mystery behind this mildred splitting.=

> Every library over 128 functions (system) are splited in two libs. WHY?=

> well I think, because there are no more than 128 tokens allowed per one=

> library.

I was thinking this too.  And of course they do not say in the docs anywh=
ere
how many commands are allowed in each library.

And really in the system libs, they are splitted after #127 commsnd.
#0 is not used in any library I looked at.  (and I looked at each one I
have)

> And thats why Mildred occupies the library numbers 15 and 16, but becau=
se
> MiniMildred is located to this number you most likely have not found th=
at
> one.

Well, I don't have Mini-Mildred (as I understand it is just a duplicate o=
f
some of the Mildred commands from the big library.)

> Because you DON'T NEED to use these simultaneusly.

Yes - but how does the Blitz compiler make these commands work then? =

Because if it is reading the numbers the same as I am, then the Mildred
commands >127 are telling it to use a library that does not exist  (or th=
e
wrong library, if I did have #16) - or does the MakeDefLibs automatically=

split Mildred into 2 parts using Library #16 for the second part?

Because surely the whole Mildred library DOES work...

But, then why are the system librarys split into 2 parts...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




