@NODE "Mail_135" "Re: The token things."
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 3 Mar 1999 15:27:31 +0000
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Wed, 03 Mar 1999 17:23:08 +0300
Subject: Re: The token things.
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 03-Mar-99, Paul wrote.

>  > Yes - but how does the Blitz compiler make these commands work then?=
 =

>  > Because if it is reading the numbers the same as I am, then the Mild=
red
>  > commands >127 are telling it to use a library that does not exist  (=
or
the
>  > wrong library, if I did have #16) - or does the MakeDefLibs
automatically
>  > split Mildred into 2 parts using Library #16 for the second part?
>  > =

>  > Because surely the whole Mildred library DOES work...
>  > =

>  > But, then why are the system librarys split into 2 parts...
>  =

>  Interesting questions Curt. Mildred is one lib numbered 15. When I had=

>  to modify the makedeflibs it seemed to me that all it did was allocate=

>  enough space in the deflibs file to store the whole object file + 4
>  bytes, and those 4 bytes are used to tell it how many bytes are in the=

>  object file. I don't know what happens after that, or why other libs
>  are split into two parts. Maybe it's just to make things friendlier or=

>  something.

Well It's quite obvious. Because those "overflowed" commands will occupy
the area of the next library and thus you can't use it to anything.
But using library as splited will occupy the next library number correctl=
y.
Now if someone is using same lib number you will see that there is alread=
y
library of this number. If you just overflow it. It will work unless
somebody installs library to the next library number from your lib.

Now this one wasn't discovered, because the next lib was MiniMildred.

-- =


            Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen   A1260 50MB 4.5GB 2X 56k HP LaserJet4L
            EMail: sami.naatanen@dlc.fi




