@NODE "Mail_147" "Re: Text on a chunky display?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 22 Mar 1999 09:28:40 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 22 Mar 99 09:27:59 +0000
Subject: Re: Text on a chunky display?
Encoding: 7bit

> How can I display text easily on a chunky display?  My game is running on a
> 640x480x256color screen using Mildred1.46
> 
> I'd like to display lots of text on the fly, but right now I'm resorting to
> creating a shape object for each letter and number which is getting
> expensive.

Surely it will still be `expensive' if you were to hold a font in ram
and render it as required? Without doing planar-to-chunky conversion
to render the characters from 2-colour planar to 256-colour chunky,
which would be dam slow (an expense), I can't see another way around
it. The way you're already doing it is imo the better approach.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_148" "Text on a chunky display?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 22 Mar 1999 05:06:49 +0000
From: "blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie" <slebed@earthlink.net>
Date: Sun, 21 Mar 1999 21:00:58 -0800
Subject: Text on a chunky display?

Hello,

How can I display text easily on a chunky display?  My game is running on a
640x480x256color screen using Mildred1.46

I'd like to display lots of text on the fly, but right now I'm resorting to
creating a shape object for each letter and number which is getting
expensive.

Any ideas??

Kind regards

Stephen Lebed
slebed@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_149" "Re: Text on a chunky display?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 22 Mar 1999 19:44:15 +0000
From: david white <david@tara-1.demon.co.uk>
Date: Mon, 22 Mar 1999 19:39:02 +0100
Subject: Re: Text on a chunky display?
Encoding: binary

Hi, Paul

On 22-Mar-99, you wrote:

>>  How can I display text easily on a chunky display? My game is running on
>>  a 640x480x256color screen using Mildred1.46
>>  
>>  I'd like to display lots of text on the fly, but right now I'm resorting
>>  to creating a shape object for each letter and number which is getting
>>  expensive.
> 
> Surely it will still be `expensive' if you were to hold a font in ram
> and render it as required? Without doing planar-to-chunky conversion
> to render the characters from 2-colour planar to 256-colour chunky,
> which would be dam slow (an expense), I can't see another way around
> it. The way you're already doing it is imo the better approach.
> 
Regards
-- 

I'd Agree. Because people have a lot of memory anyway nowadays, and the
amount required for 50-100 or so small characters is negligible. Also, using shapes
 for characters gives you a bit more control over them IMHO, with the added 
bonus of being able to add cool effects to your text as well :)))   And if
you create a queue for anything you're printing and use Mqblit, you can just
plonk it down and forget about it,  and just unqueue it when you want to get
rid of it. Seems worthwhile to me :))

Regards




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_150" "Re: Text on a chunky display?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 23:52:46 +0000
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Wed, 24 Mar 1999 10:58:48 +1200
Subject: Re: Text on a chunky display?

On 23-Mar-99, david white wrote:
 > 
> I'd Agree. Because people have a lot of memory anyway nowadays, and
the
> amount required for 50-100 or so small characters is negligible. Also,
> using shapes
> for characters gives you a bit more control over them IMHO, with the
> added bonus of being able to add cool effects to your text as well
 
  Yes, you can easily do fonts in many colours, dropshadows etc, instead
of just the boring one colour font!

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
     



@ENDNODE
