@NODE "Mail_162" "Re: Tasks and Processes"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 5 Mar 1999 22:21:55 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
        OldBlitzList <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>,
        NewBlitzList <blitz-list@egroups.com>
Date: Fri, 05 Mar 1999 16:11:37 -0500
Subject: Re: Tasks and Processes

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.


--BOUNDARY.1748393168.1

Hi Loki

On 05-Mar-99, Loki wrote:

> FindTask_() is ok, and works with `Blitz2' ... But wont find any of my
> executables! :((((... Why?

Maybe they are "Processes" rather than tasks...

Also, using FindTask_ you must keep in mind that it IS case sensitive.

And if run from the CLI, the taskname would be something like:

"CLI[8]SYS:Utilities/MultiView" or whatever you typed into the CLI to run
it...
> 
> Oh also,.. is there any way to rename your task, I`ve noticed that XOpa
> usually shows tasks at the original filename,.. but is there a way
> to make sure the taskname will be exactly what you want it to be,
> and not something different if the user has renamed the file?

Well, once it is run, I don't think you can change the name.

But here is a function that tells you what your program's name is.  Maybe
this is helpful.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748393168.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="progname"

Function.s ProgsName{}
If FromCLI=-1
  *stringbuffer = AllocMem_(255, 0)
  suc.l=GetProgramName_(*stringbuffer,255)
  If suc
    pname$=Peek$(*stringbuffer)
  EndIf
  FreeMem_ *stringbuffer,255
Else
  pname$=Peek$(Peek.l(FindTask_(0)+$B0)+4)
EndIf

End Function

--BOUNDARY.1748393168.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_163" "Re: Tasks and Processes"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 6 Mar 1999 12:42:10 +0000
From: Brucey <brucey@thenet.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Tasks and Processes
Date: Sat, 6 Mar 1999 12:42:10 +0000

>Also, using FindTask_ you must keep in mind that it IS case sensitive.
>
>And if run from the CLI, the taskname would be something like:
>
>"CLI[8]SYS:Utilities/MultiView" or whatever you typed into the CLI to run
>it...

I find that FindTask_(0)  works perfectly well.  'Zero' being the calling
program.
And, if you want to change the Priority, use -

        psetting.w = SetTaskPri_(FindTask_(0),num)

where - psetting now contains the NEW Priority level,
        num is the value you want to set.


