@NODE "Mail_177" "Re: Subject set, as ezmlm doesnt accept empty subject fields :-)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 11:30:49 +0000
From: "David McMinn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 1999 11:29:11 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Subject set, as ezmlm doesnt accept empty subject fields :-)

> What code do you need to put in to be able to use your prog with version=
?
> 
> I do this:
> 
> goto skipthis
> even
>    dc.b "VER$: blah blah"
> even
> .skipthis:
> 
> This at least makes the info appear in a text viewer, if it reads in exe
> files. Without the goto it crashes miserably :-)
>
> What does dc.b do btw?

 It just sticks the bytes directly into your program, at the location they=
 are 
in the program. So if you do what you did above, in the middle of some cod=
e, 
the processor tries to execute it - crash, boom, bang. Another way that it=
 
might work is to define a string which has the "VER$: blah" in it. A bit 
easier, but don't know if it works all the time, i.e. if anything in your 
program has a version string *before* the strings are stored (usually put =
at 
the end by the compiler) then those version strings may be used.


