@NODE "Mail_180" "Strings, More Strings and Dynamic linked lists"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 22 Mar 1999 01:29:16 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Strings, More Strings and Dynamic linked lists
Date: Mon, 22 Mar 1999 01:32:02 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hey all blitz gurus...anyone got an idea how to fix this??

I have an old dynamic linked list library (well, an include really), which
I`ve used in the past okay (just for messing about with really) and now I
want to use it in a real application. Only I can`t figure out how to
deallocate strings.

Basically, I have all the same functions as the normal blitz lists, but when
it comes to killing an item, I can simply freemem the list memory, but the
.s variables in the list are just long word pointers. What I need to be able
to do is to see if any of the items in the list have strings in them, and
deallocate them before I free the list item`s memory. Otherwise I`ll end up
with a load of disconnecting strings taking up extra memory until END is
reached in the program.

Could I fix this by making it a library?? Is there a way to access strings
in libraries...i.e., call a string library function to properly deallocate
them, or will I have to do some dodge patching of blitz (i.e., getting the
allocated mem base, and stepping through it looking for my strings and then
deallocate them)


Slightly Puzzled,

Dave


P.s. I can share the source if it`ll help........





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_181" "Re: Strings, More Strings and Dynamic linked lists"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 22 Mar 1999 01:38:05 +0000
Date:	Sun, 21 Mar 1999 21:37:23 -0400 (AST)
Sender: ah210@chebucto.ns.ca
From:	John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
Subject: Re: Strings, More Strings and Dynamic linked lists

Hi Dave,

> .s variables in the list are just long word pointers. What I need to be able
> to do is to see if any of the items in the list have strings in them, and
> deallocate them before I free the list item`s memory. Otherwise I`ll end up
> with a load of disconnecting strings taking up extra memory until END is
> reached in the program.

Couldn't you just get the address of the string, and scan through ram from
there until you get a null char?  Then you could calculate the size of the
string and use that with Freemem_ to free that memory.  Or is that what
you're trying to avoid doing? :)

