From: "Tony Rolfe" <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Organization: Edgewater Motel, Burrill Lake, NSW 2539 Australia
Date: 22 Mar 99 12:54:29 +1000
Subject: Re: Strings, More Strings and Dynamic linked lists
Encoding: 7bit

On Mon, 22 Mar 1999 01:32:02 -0000 Dave said:
> Hey all blitz gurus...anyone got an idea how to fix this??
> 
> I have an old dynamic linked list library (well, an include really), which
> I`ve used in the past okay (just for messing about with really) and now I
> want to use it in a real application. Only I can`t figure out how to
> deallocate strings.
> 
> Basically, I have all the same functions as the normal blitz lists, but when
> it comes to killing an item, I can simply freemem the list memory, but the
> .s variables in the list are just long word pointers. What I need to be able
> to do is to see if any of the items in the list have strings in them, and
> deallocate them before I free the list item`s memory. Otherwise I`ll end up
> with a load of disconnecting strings taking up extra memory until END is
> reached in the program.
> 
I don't think there is a problem here.  If you do a

 Dim List Fred.thing(1000), 

where the .thing type contains strings, then another 

Dim List Fred(any number you like)

will deallocate all the memory associated with the list (including the
strings), before recreating the new headers.

At least, it seems to in my program.  I've not got huge amounts of
memory to spare and have never run out of memory mid-stream.  I do the
Dim List ReportLines(some number) all over my code (this is my default
GTScroller array).   If there were strings left lying about I'm sure
I'd have run out of memory at least occasionally.

Cheers

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+4Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater


