@NODE "Mail_210" "Re: SetProtection_ ()"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 16:07:22 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 16:05:11 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 1 Mar 99 16:04:28 +0000
Subject: Re: SetProtection_ ()
Encoding: 7bit

> Erm, it depends. In Microsoft style progamming, even a flag (that can only ever be true or false) is a longword (or doubleword as they call it) anyway since the result is (generally) going to be a long, you might aswell keep the operators long aswell. It really depends on what you need it for, and how large numbers you're going to use.
> 
> LSL, means logical shift left. It moves all the bits a certain
> number of places to the left, efectivly oubleing the value each
> times. For example %00100010 LSL 1 (the same as *2, only faster) =
> %01000100, and the number has doubled :o>
> LSR, means logical shift right, and is the opposite.

LSL is Logarithmic shift left, not logical shift left. Same for right.
Mind you, I don't pretend to know what logarithmic means. :-}

There is also ASL and ASR which are arithmetic shifts. The difference
is that with a logarithmic shift the high or low end of the shifted
value is filled with 0's, whereas the arithmetic shift maintains the
sign-extend.

-- 
Paul.

