Hello James.

On 28-Feb-99, James L Boyd wrote:

>> Logically OR the things together. For example, to turn on only executa=
ble

> Yeah, that's what I was doing before, but obviously it failed because
> of the above...

> This works here - just one little thing...I made a variable, bits.l, to=

> hold the OR'd flags, cos it was gonna be a struggle to fit it all on on=
e line
> (lousy TED!), but does bits need to be an .l? I don't really know what'=
s
> happening with those LSL's and stuff... ;)

Erm, it depends. In Microsoft style progamming, even a flag (that can onl=
y ever be true or false) is a longword (or doubleword as they call it) an=
yway since the result is (generally) going to be a long, you might aswell=
 keep the operators long aswell. It really depends on what you need it fo=
r, and how large numbers you're going to use.

LSL, means logical shift left. It moves all the bits a certain number of =
places to the left, efectivly oubleing the value each times. For example =
%00100010 LSL 1 (the same as *2, only faster) =3D %01000100, and the numb=
er has doubled :o>
LSR, means logical shift right, and is the opposite.


Regards
