>I think you're confusing Copyrights, with intellectual property rights.
>Copyright, as the word suggests, is the right to copy (hence distribute)=
 any
>given material. Intellectual property, means who "owns" the material in
>question.

>So if you do get arround to finishing soething, it will be your intellec=
tual
>property, but the (most likely exclusive, meaning no one else can lawful=
ly
>obtain it) copyright of the publisher.


  I sorry, but this is entirely incorrect.  The copywrite IS esentially t=
he
ownership.  The origional copywrite on anything belongs to the creator of=
 it
unless he/she is being paid by another entity for the time used in the
creative process or for the copywrite(s) themselves.  The mere act of
creating something entitles the creator to the copywrite in most countrys=
however it is far more secure if legal papers are drawn up to cover it be=
cause
any enforcement will require proof of ownership.  A publisher has no righ=
ts
to the material except those which are granted under contract or by sale =
by
the copywrite owner.  The copywrite owner may indeed choose to sell only
limited rights to a publisher.  These limits may be almost anything the
owner wishes (with the provisio of course that if he/she is two unreasona=
ble
there may be no agreement reached and thus no sale.  Common restrictions =
are
to have the rights revert back to the origional owner in the event of the=

dissolution of the business or lack of action after a specified period of=

time.  Another common one is a copywright "lease" in which a second party=

pays for the use of the rights for a period of time.  Other common provis=
ios
include the owner retaining the rights but selling the right to use them
(either exclusively or non-exclusively) for a royalty-per-unit or a flat
fee or some other consideration.  Many agreements include several of the
preceeding provisios, and of course there are others to numerous to menti=
on
here.  One other which does bear mentioning however, is the inclusion of
controlling restrictions on method of sale, area, time, target markets
and quality of product.

  So you see, outright sale of the rights is not necessary and often not
desireable, especially if a degree of control is desired by the origional=

owner.




>In this case, Blitz2 is the intellectual property of Mark Sibly and Simo=
n
>Armstrong, also know as ACID software. They will own this software until=
 70
>years after their deaths (After which period ownership claims must be
>renewed).


  The period of time is 70 years after the origional creation of the
copywrited material, and not all copywrites are renewable.
  The rights then fall into the public domaign.


>The copyright for Blitz2 is probably spread arround on some 6 or so diff=
erent
>companies at least (to handle worldwide distribution). The thing to do i=
s
find

  No. There is likely to be only one owner of the copywrite as jointly ow=
ned
copywrites are extremely rare, at least at the corporate level.


>Mark Sibly, and ask him if there are any exclusve copyrights (Or someone=
 in
>New Zealand could phone and ask the patent buruea), if there is no exclu=
sive
>copyrights, just get Mark Sibly to wave his rights on the software, and =
it
>will be public domaine.


  Whoever ownes the copywrite is of course restricted in what they can do=
 by
any previous legal agreements they may have made.  Also remember that
copywrites generally are transferable and considered real property, but t=
he
granted use of copywrites may not be, depending on the legal agreement ma=
de.
If a company actually outright OWNS copywrites they will got to the credi=
tors
if the company is liquidated.  If a company has merely purchased rights t=
o
use or duplicat copywrited material then these rights MAY die with the
company unless they are specifically transferable.


