@NODE "Mail_281" "Re: r u receiving?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 18 Mar 1999 02:32:00 +0000
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Wed, 17 Mar 1999 20:28:17 +0500
Subject: Re: r u receiving?

On 17-Mar-99, Dave flashed:


>My friend worked for a company that is creating database software for the
>NHS, and as far as I`m aware, he doesn`t own any of the program he has
>created and has no `rights` to it at all, as when the company was taken over
>by another company and he was fired, they took over the software and all
>rights to it. Why did I tell you that...your wondering....because I wondered
> if I started up a company with a friend, and we created some software, and
>then we sold the company down the line (or it went bankrupt)...who would own
>the software?? And who owns the source code??


   If the company owned it and was sold, who owned it then would depend on
the terms of the sale (such as whether the company was sold as a unit or
piecemeal, or whether certain propertys were specifically excluded from
the sale.  Any excluded propertys would then still be owned by the former
owners.
  I a company went bankrupt, any copywrites owned by it would be transfered
to the reciever, whould decide under the laws of the land whether to sell
the rights,and give the proceeds to the creditors or to transfer the rights
directly to the creditors, or to sell the rights as a part of the whole
company as one integral sale.


  A little word of advice to every programer.  NEVER relenquish the rights
to your creations unless it is the only way to make the profits worth your
while.  It is much better to make carefully crafted agreements entailing
royalties or profit sharing or sell liscenses priced according to value
entailed, and keep the permanent rights yourself.  Only sell rights in their
entirety if it is made VERY worth your while, unless of course you don't
think the property is valuable.

  And if you program something which you wish to give to others to be helpful
and neighborly, carefully consider whether to give away the ownership rights
or just the limited rights of use.  If you don't care what people do with it
or don't want to be bothered, just state that you are giving it to the public
by putting it in the public domaign.  If however you wish to maintain some
control over how, when, where and by whom it is used, then your release
should state that the property is copywrited freeware, and you should clearly
state any restrictions on distribution and/or useage.  Your copywrited
freeware cover document should escentually constitute a liscense agreement in
which you are the liscense grantor and the user is the liscensee.

  All software should include a disclaimor exempting you from damages to the
full extent allowed by law, although this won't protect you at all if it is
provable that you had malevolent intent an/or were willfully neglegent.
  Relenquishing ownership by release to the public domaign and including a
well-worded disclaimer will usually protect you quite well as long as no
illegal content is included.



I hope this helps a few people understand the possibilities better.


Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)




@ENDNODE
