From: Thomas Cobb <tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk>
Subject: Re: Passing Information!
Encoding: 7bit

Simon Archer wrote:

> I watched as Loki entered 'Passing Information!' into the terminal. "What's a Syntax Error?" asked Loki
>
>  L>    Anyone know a way to pass information between 2 programs?
>  L> IE, To pass a string from one task to another seemlessly.
>
> The easiest way would be each application uses Arexx.

> The right way would be exec msg ports...

Arexx ports are just souped up exec msg ports.  I don't see why one is more correct than the other.
As an alternative, if you can't be bothered with ports, have you tried using the PIPE?
You can create your own pipe just like an ordinary file - something like openfile(0,"PIPE:filename")
would do.

    Thom



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_303" "Re: Passing Information!"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 3 Mar 1999 00:00:57 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 02 Mar 1999 15:21:40 -0500
Subject: Re: Passing Information!

Hi Thomas

On 02-Mar-99, Thomas Cobb wrote:
> Simon Archer wrote:

>>  The easiest way would be each application uses Arexx.
> 
>> The right way would be exec msg ports...
> 
> Arexx ports are just souped up exec msg ports. I don't see why one is
more
> correct than the other. 

Arexx commands must go through RexxNaster - which means, of course, the user
must have it, and it must be running.  Best used if you want to allow other
programs to be able to get in on the communication as well as your own.  Or
control an already existing program, such as MultiView.

Msg ports go direct between the two programs.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
