@NODE "Mail_337" "New animation format"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 03:36:01 +0000
From: Stephen Lebed <slebed@earthlink.net>
Date: Mon, 22 Mar 1999 19:29:39 -0800
Subject: New animation format

Hi All,

Sorry for the long letter...

Since there doesn't seem to be an animation format out there that will work
on chunky displays, I've decided to write my own.  I've looked into XFA,
and while it does play very fast on a planar screen, it docs say that there
is a performance hit using its cybergraphx commands.

I'm going to open this up to everyone.  I'm not the swiftest programmer out
there and I could use help optimizing it.

Below is an outline of my proposal...

My target is a 640x480 display in 256 colors.
Frame rate is 16fps or better
It should be able to play off a 4x cdrom.
Sync audio with the ability to drop frames in order to sustain the frame
rate.

For better or worse, these are my design goals...

Please give me any opinions you have, positive or negative...

The idea is to read in the header info which would contain image size, audio
setting, and keyframe timing and file offset information.

The first frame is decompressed to a hidden buffer, then every other scan
line is copied to the visible display.

The timer is reset and the first audio chunk is started.

The next frame header is read.   This would contain the compression info (ie
horizontal RLE,vertical RLE, No compression)

The frame delta is read in and decompressed.

When decompressed to the alternating set of scanlines, it is checked against
the timer to see if its early, if so it would be displayed at the right
time.
If not then it is displayed, and the filepointer is advanced to the next
keyframe.

This would continue until the animation is finished.

This is essentally what anim is now minus the chunky, audio, and timing
support.


Some math stuff:  640x480 display = 307200 bytes
                     If I display every other scanline       /2  = 153600
bytes  
            16frames/second playback   = 2457600 bytes moved / second
4x cdrom = 614400 bytes/ second transfer rate (problebly not the actual rate
though)

2457600 bytes / 614400 bytes = 4  This would be our compression ratio needed
to make this work.

I understand that these are mathmatical properties and that realworld tests
will fall sort of my numbers here.

What is your thoughts to this?

Stephen Lebed
slebed@earthlink.net
     




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_338" "Re: New animation format"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 19:48:36 +0000
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 1999 15:36:29 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: New animation format
Encoding: 7bit

Paul wrote:
> > My target is a 640x480 display in 256 colors.
> > Frame rate is 16fps or better
> 
> Good luck! ;-)

This would be impossible on anything but the fastest amigas with fast
CD-Rom and a fast gfx card. Most Amiga game anims are about postage
stamp size for a good reason ;)
 
> > 2457600 bytes / 614400 bytes = 4  This would be our compression
> >ratio needed to make this work.
> 
> Not to mention that you need additional time to actually do the
> decompression and rendering to the display.

And the time it actually takes to parse the data from the drive via
the file system which can cause a great deal of lag. Working with
asyncronous I/O would help but it's still a lot of data to be parsing.

> I dont think you will get 16fps at that resolution from a 4xCDrom or
> likely any speed cdrom.

You'd need a Zorro3 type gfx bus (or better) to even render that much
data at that speed. Thats without rendering and parsing.

Best thing to do is work in lowres until you manage to get 320x240 size
anims running at a good speed. Then when the technique is optimized you
could try 640x480 mode for very high end Amigas.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >




@ENDNODE
