@NODE "Mail_340" "Re: New animation format"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 25 Mar 1999 14:02:04 +0000
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Thu, 25 Mar 1999 13:11:44 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: New animation format
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Stephen.

On 23-Mar-99, Stephen Lebed wrote:
> Hi All,

> Sorry for the long letter...

> Since there doesn't seem to be an animation format out there that will =
work
> on chunky displays, I've decided to write my own.  I've looked into XFA=
> and while it does play very fast on a planar screen, it docs say that t=
here
> is a performance hit using its cybergraphx commands.

There are many chunky animation formats out there, QuickTime, MPEG and AV=
I just to name a few.

> I'm going to open this up to everyone.  I'm not the swiftest programmer=
 out
> there and I could use help optimizing it.

> Below is an outline of my proposal...

> My target is a 640x480 display in 256 colors.
> Frame rate is 16fps or better
> It should be able to play off a 4x cdrom.

Erm, right. As IF that's ever gonna happen.

> The idea is to read in the header info which would contain image size, =
audio
> setting, and keyframe timing and file offset information.

This is a good idea.

> The first frame is decompressed to a hidden buffer, then every other sc=
an
> line is copied to the visible display.

This is where you loose me, if you only use every other line, then what's=
 the point in doing it in a high res ? If you must halve the size, just d=
o 640x200 with correct perspective. It also gives a nice CinemaScope feel=
ing.

> The timer is reset and the first audio chunk is started.

Erm, okay.

> The next frame header is read.   This would contain the compression inf=
o (ie
> horizontal RLE,vertical RLE, No compression)

In order to do vertical RLE you would have to build the picture from left=
 to right (as opposed to the usual top to bottom)

> Some math stuff:  640x480 display =3D 307200 bytes
>                     If I display every other scanline       /2  =3D 153=
600
> bytes  =

>            16frames/second playback   =3D 2457600 bytes moved / second
> 4x cdrom =3D 614400 bytes/ second transfer rate (problebly not the actu=
al rate
> though)

> 2457600 bytes / 614400 bytes =3D 4  This would be our compression ratio=
 needed
> to make this work.

> I understand that these are mathmatical properties and that realworld t=
ests
> will fall sort of my numbers here.

> What is your thoughts to this?

Well AGA can't stream 2.5 Megabytes per second to CHIP RAM so it would on=
ly work on graphics boards for starters. I think you should go for a much=
 smaller target, one you might eventually reach. Another point is if you =
need a 4:1 comppression ratio you're going to have to do lossy compressio=
n, so it won't nessecarrily be a better quality picture than one in a low=
er resolution would be.


Regards
-- =


