@NODE "Mail_344" "re: My Tuppence Worth Again"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 13 Mar 1999 21:32:02 +0000
From: Terry & Tom Stone <tjstone@wkpowerlink.com>
Date: Wed, 02 Sep 1992 14:58:12 +0500
Organization: WKPowerlink
Subject: re: My Tuppence Worth Again
Encoding: quoted-printable


>    Some of you guys( and girls Liz ;-) ) obviously know an awful lot ab=
out
>the miggy and about blitz, and you stride off into the distance leaving =
some
>of us behind, not knowing what the Hell is going on.
>    My point - not sure, really, but having two lists suggests that you
>could perhaps have a beginners list( with Ye Great Gurus giving advice f=
rom
>on high ) and also an advanced user list which we mere mortals can read =
and
>hope to aspire to.  It's only a suggestion, but I'd be intrerested to se=
e
>what people think.

   Jes, =


   Personally I think the one list works fine for me.

   Each person is at a specific "experience level" and chooses how far th=
ey
   want to go with learning more about Blitz and the Amiga in general.

   All the advanced topics helps those that want to take in everything
   and push their programming skills to the limits.

   For my self, I liked the idea of writing games without having to write=

   so many common functions from scratch and choose to use Blitz mode for=
=3D
   the most part. There have been many interesting discussions on making =
games
   in Amiga mode only/supporting GFX cards, etc but I made a decision to
   stick with Blitz mode for my "Valhalla-like" game knowing that it woul=
d
   not be the "latest/greatest" game in terms of innovation or graphics.
   In my heart I still believe that if a game is done well (good story, p=
uzzles
   with reasonable graphics (as good as Valhalla's if not better)), then
   I would be satified with the results and hopefully some gamer's would
   still enjoy it.

   This "game scope" suites me fine since with many other interests and a=
 full
   time job, I don't have time to change my direction or the game will ne=
ver
   get done.

   So....

   Naturally most of the discussions on this list do not relate to what I=

   need to do.  Much of it is "beyond me" only because they are not areas=

   I am familiar with (chucky to planar/intuition programming, interleavi=
ng)
   and plan to avoid focusing on because of time constraints; never-the-l=
ess
   it good to keep up on what is possible and that is why I still read wh=
at
   is talked about.  From time to time someone would mention something th=
at
   I had not even considered but would file away in the back of my mind
   in case in the future I ran into a road block and needed to consider t=
his =

   alternative or suggestion.

   For the most part, I have remained quite since this listed provided me=

   with almost all my answers to help me get my game engine up and runnin=
g
   (first full level to go through final QA this weekend) over a year ago=
=2E

   Yes, it true that many of the topics are beyond me (because I choose n=
ot =

   to learn these areas), but as a beginner when I ask questions, this li=
st
   was almost always helpful and very willing to help beginners. =


   In many respects I an still a beginner Blitz programmer, sticking to B=
litz
   mode and library routines which helped for most of the game.  Trying t=
o
   write a 4-way scroller from scratch was the hardest part for me.  So I=
 rarely
   help other programmers out since I don't know the answers, but have he=
lped
   from time-to-time.

>    Finally, Long live the Amiga and all that - maybe one day I'll be ab=
le
>to afford to put some stuff into the tower I bought and hopefully it won=
't
>be bankrupt stock.  Keep going folks - before getting online these lists=

>were my first port of call on the AF coverdisc each month - give yoursel=
ves
>a pat on the back( or whatever part of your anatomy you like ) as you ha=
ve
>helped keep at least one person interested.

Yes, I would like to thank the people on this list too for without your h=
elp
I would have given up on Blitz along time ago.  I had no idea how much wo=
rk
it takes to make a quality game and certainly have alot more respect for
game progammers these days especially those that have to keep up on the
latest/greatest innovations to stay in the "now".  I now know that game
programming is not for me, but I will definately see my current game thro=
ugh
to the end.

Thanks

Tom




