@NODE "Mail_345" "Re: My Tuppence Worth Again"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 14 Mar 1999 16:33:45 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 14 Mar 1999 10:16:50 -0500
Subject: Re: My Tuppence Worth Again

Hi Tom,

On 02-Sep-92, Terry & Tom Stone wrote:

>   Jes, 
> 
>   Personally I think the one list works fine for me.

Yes, I don't think having a "beginner's" list and an "advanced" list is a
good idea. 

>   All the advanced topics helps those that want to take in everything
>   and push their programming skills to the limits.

A lot of what I have learned has come from those postings I didn't
understand -
I have often saw an answer to something that used an OS routine, and it
would inspire me to learn it.

And even if you don't understand something, at least it can often give you
an idea or a new way to approach something that you had not thought about.

If it wasn't for the Blitz list, I'd still be flailing about in the manual
trying to figure out what was going on...
> 
>   For my self, I liked the idea of writing games without having to write
>   so many common functions from scratch and choose to use Blitz mode for=
>   the most part. There have been many interesting discussions on making
> games
>   in Amiga mode only/supporting GFX cards, etc but I made a decision to
>   stick with Blitz mode for my "Valhalla-like" game knowing that it would
>   not be the "latest/greatest" game in terms of innovation or graphics.

I'd like to say again, that there is nothing at all wrong with programming
in whatever method works for you.  As long as you know the limitations of
the method you are using, and it suits your goal, just go with it.

There are limitations to games done the OS way with GFX card support too,
mainly that they will require at least an 030x50 and some fast mem, plus
AGA or a GFX card of course.

>   In my heart I still believe that if a game is done well (good story,
> puzzles
>   with reasonable graphics (as good as Valhalla's if not better)), then
>   I would be satified with the results and hopefully some gamer's would
>   still enjoy it.

Yes, exactly  (if they have a system it can run on)

> never-the-less
>   it good to keep up on what is possible and that is why I still read
what
>   is talked about.  From time to time someone would mention something
that
>   I had not even considered but would file away in the back of my mind
>   in case in the future I ran into a road block and needed to consider
>  this alternative or suggestion.

> Yes, I would like to thank the people on this list too for without your
> help I would have given up on Blitz along time ago. 

Goes for me too!

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




