@NODE "Mail_373" "Mildred v1.47"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 15:48:45 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 23 Mar 99 15:39:37 +0000
Subject: Mildred v1.47
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Folks.

After a fairly quiet period for Mildred recently (that time of the
month), a new version has just been finished. It's been uploaded and
should be online shortly at http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk as and
when demon internet see fit to get their finger out and update it. <g>

Apart from adding a [,BitmapNum.w] parameter to the MPoint commands,
the main additions are CustomOffset lists and zooms. The MScroll
commands and the MSScroll commands have had an optional parameter
added to the syntax - CustomOffsets.l. You can use this to point to a
list of custom values which will be used on a per-line basis to modify
the scroll operation during processing. The newtype for an entry for a
single row in the scroll would be as follows:

NewType.._Scroll
  Width.w
  X1Offset.w
  X2Offset.w
  SourceModulo.w
End NewType

If you were going to do a scroll that was 50 rows high, you would need
an array of 50 items such as Dim _ScrollItems._Scroll(50). You then
pass the base of this array (&_ScrollItems(0)) as CustomOffsets.l to
something like MScroll, and the list of values will be used. Each
entry in the array represents a single row of the scroll. You can
modify the width on a per-line basis, you can change the X coordinate
of the start of the source line being read, as well as the X
coordinate at which to output in the destination for each row. Using
these is it possible, for example, to scroll a triangle or a circle.
Note that the offsets are relative to the previous line, not absolute
(unless it's stated so in the docs). SourceModulo can be used to
produce other copperlist type effects such as turning an image upside
down realtime or doing a verticle zoom.

This brings me onto the other addition. MZoom, MZoomShape,
MZoomBitmapToShape and MZoomShapeToBitmap have been added. Source
coordinates and X and Y increments have to be specified as .quick
values, along with integer operation width, height, and dest coords.
It's not quite the same as just saying to zoom from one bounding box
to another like in amos for example, but rather gives a bit more
control over the magnification accuracy. There is also, as with the
MScrolls and MSScrolls, a CustomOffsets.l parameter, to which you can
supply a list of custom values to use for each line of the zoom, which
is when things start to get fun. ;-) Each element in the array should
be the following newtype:

NewType._Zoom
  Width.w
  DestXOffset.w
  SourceXOffset.q
  XAddOffset.q
  YAddOffset.q
End NewType

And again to set up a list appropriate for a zoom that is 50 pixels
high in the destination you would simple do something like Dim
_ZoomData._Zoom(50) and pass &_ZoomData(0) as CustomOffsets.l to the
token. For each line of the zoom the custom values will be read in and
used. You can change the operation width, add an offset to the
destination X coordinate, add an offset to the source X coordinate
(.q), and also add offsets to the X and Y adders, whicih means you can
progressible [de]magnify as the zoom proceeds from top to bottom
and/or left to right, with which it should be possible to emulate a
sort of perspective floor effect (although a similar thing can be done
with MScroll and a custom-offsets list).

Three new demos (actually 5 programs) have also been added to the
website demonstrating how to use the zooms and the custom-offset
lists for zoom and scroll. Note that the zooms are optimised so if you
supply integer (no decimal part) x or y adders it will perform faster
(especially if XAdd is an integer). It can also be faster if width is
a multilpe of 4 or even 16, but that doesn't apply to when using a
custom-offset list.

Anyway, its all documented in the updated documentation (where else),
and the new library version and demo programs should be on-line
imminently.

Enjoy,


 --  .Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_374" "Mildred v1.43"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 2 Mar 1999 20:59:39 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 2 Mar 1999 20:58:23 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 2 Mar 99 20:58:09 +0000
Subject: Mildred v1.43
Encoding: 7bit

Hi folks.

I've just finished v1.43 of Mildred and am just uploading it as we
speak. If you're using Mildred then there are some important things
you need to know about this update. Only one token has been added,
necessarily. About 40 tokens have been removed!

You must save off your programs as ascii text BEFORE you install the
new version. Then install the new version, and finally load in your
ascii texts. This will sort out most tokenisation problems.

However, the changes are more than just the removal of tokens. The
functionality of many tokens has been merged into others.

Please aquire the Mildred.Guide documentation and READ the
`information' bit. The changes are detailed extensively as well as
explaining what you will need to do in order to ensure compatibility
in your programs.

Most of the old `plural' versions of command have been scrapped, such
as for example MFreeShapes, MUseBitmaps, MMakeStencils, etc. Their
functionality has been put into the `singular' versions as extra
syntax possibilities. You can still handle `all' and a `range' of
objects. If you've used any of those tokens in your program you will
have a small amount of manual work to do to change them.

Also almost all of the `A' and `Q' variations of the particle commands
have been merged into what used to be the `word' versions. The
particle format is now chosen using the new token, MParticleFormat,
which you WILL need to add you any programs that you have used
particle commands in.

A few tokens haven't had their functionality moved, but simply deleted
altogether. They were naff, tacky and cluttering things. Examples of
this are M040c2pUsage, MMidHandle, MBitmapMidOrigin, MCopyHandle,
MCopyOrigin and MFlushTable. If you have used any of these you will
need to do a small amount of manual recoding. Also MReMapUsingShape
and MReMapShapeUsingShape have been scrapped. Use a remapped scroll or
blit instead.

When you get the v1.43 library archive also get the v1.43
documentation and read the information about these changes, and for
heaven's sake make sure you save your progs as ascii *before* you
install the new lib. <g>

Any problems with these changes please mail me. These changes are
necessary to tidy things up and prepare for the future. Hopefully
there will be no need for further changes to the tokens of this
nature. All of the demo programs on the support site will shortly be
updated to be compliant with the new version.

Cheers,

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
