@NODE "Mail_380" "Re: Memory Locations"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 14 Mar 1999 20:57:08 +0000
From: "Anders Hasselqvist" <hassel@acc.umu.se>
Subject: Re: Memory Locations
Date: Sun, 14 Mar 1999 21:56:33 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: quoted-printable

From: Gareth Griffiths <gaz@jokerd.idps.co.uk>

>
> #DecodeModule# 1,<ADDRESS>
> #PlayModule# 1
> #MouseWait#
># End#
>
> I don't know what <ADDRESS> is for the "music.mod" file, so the =
program
>reports an error! Help.
>

? is the address operator.

You use it like this:

DecodeModule 1,?music.

music: incbin "music.mod"


Data should be at the end of your program.


Bye,

Anders Hasselqvist
hassel@acc.umu.se




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_381" "Memory Locations"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 15 Mar 1999 00:01:53 +0000
From: bml@thenet.co.uk (Simon Archer)
X-FTN-To: Gareth Griffiths
Subject: Memory Locations
Date: 14 Mar 1999 23:57:55
X-newsreader: Spot 1.3b #1534
encoding: quoted-printable

On 14 Mar 99 Gareth Griffiths wrote about 'Memory Locations'.

 GG> Hi,
 GG>    How do you find the memory location of a file which has been IncBin
 GG> 'd into code?

If you mark the point of include with a label:

mod
Incbin "Mymod.mod"

Then your code can reference the area of memory by the label:

DecodeModule 1,?mod

They're only easy if you know the answer :)

Simon Archer



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_382" "Re: Memory Locations"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 16 Mar 1999 18:49:31 +0000
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Tue, 16 Mar 1999 18:34:28 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: Memory Locations
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Gareth.

On 14-Mar-99, Gareth Griffiths wrote:
> Hi,
>   How do you find the memory location of a file which has been IncBin '=
d
> into code? =


Easy.

> My code looks like this::

> #INCDIR# "Work:Games/AB_Saga/"
> #IncBin# "title.iff"
> #IncBin# "menu.iff"
> #IncBin# "selector.bsh"
> #IncBin# "music.mod"

> #DecodeModule# 1,<ADDRESS>
> #PlayModule# 1
> #MouseWait#
> # End#

> I don't know what <ADDRESS> is for the "music.mod" file, so the program=

> reports an error! Help.

Okay, first of all you might want to either jump past those INCBIN'd thin=
gs, or just put them at the end of your program.
Now what you have to do is stick a label (for example .incmod) in the lin=
e BEFORE you INCBIN the module, e.g. =


Decodemodule 1,?incmod
[-program stuff-]
End

=2Eincmod
INCBIN "MOD.Blah"

This should work. putting a ? infront of the name of labels returns the a=
ddress of that label, just like putting an & before a variable name retur=
ns it's address. (Or is it the other way arround ?)


Regards
-- =

