@NODE "Mail_505" "Internet version checks"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 11 Mar 1999 01:19:52 +0000
From: bml@thenet.co.uk (Simon Archer)
X-FTN-To: Anton Reinauer
Subject: Internet version checks
Date: 11 Mar 1999 00:03:20
X-newsreader: Spot 1.3b #1534
encoding: quoted-printable

On 9 Mar 99 Anton Reinauer wrote about 'Internet version checks'.

 AR>   Do you mean fail as in not provide correct information, or the
 AR> Function returns a fail if you can't make a connection (for whatever
 AR> reason)? The second is what ConnectTCP{} does. =

Ho hum, what my original statement said, and I'm sure is close to what Paul=
's
routine does, is check for the existance of the socket library. Normally,=
 this
library will only be resident once the stack is up and running. This could=
 lead
to problems as Miami, at least, creates the bsdsocket.library when initiali=
sed,
not when just online. So even if the presense of the library is true, it do=
esn't
mean it's online.

The next check would be to actually open a connection on port 21 with the=
 desired
site, and if this fails it could be down to routing problems or simply not=
 online.
There isn't treally any real surefire way of checking if the user is online=
 or not
that would work in every case. The only way is to carry out as many checks=
 as
possible and hope that nothing fools the routine.

Simon Archer



@ENDNODE
