@NODE "Mail_509" "Re: Internet version checks"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 12 Mar 1999 00:50:11 +0000
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Fri, 12 Mar 1999 13:21:36 +1300
Subject: Re: Internet version checks
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 12-Mar-99, Mikkel L=F8kke wrote:
 =

>>  The next check would be to actually open a connection on port 21
with
>>  the desired site, and if this fails it could be down to routing
>>  problems or simply not online. There isn't treally any real surefire
>>  way of checking if the user is online or not that would work in
every
>>  case.

  Some info is stored in errno, if connect_ fails:

@{i}RETURN VALUES@{ui}
     If the connection or binding succeeds, 0 is returned.  Otherwise a
     -1 is returned, and a more specific error code is stored in
@{b}errno@{ub}.

@{i}ERRORS@{ui}
     The @{b}connect()@{ub} call fails if:

    @{b}[EBADF]@{ub}
          @{b}S@{ub} is not a valid descriptor.

    @{b}[EADDRNOTAVAIL]@{ub}
          The specified address is not available on this machine.

    @{b}[EAFNOSUPPORT]@{ub}
          Addresses in the specified address family cannot be used with
          this socket.

    @{b}[EISCONN]@{ub}
          The socket is already connected.

    @{b}[ETIMEDOUT]@{ub}
          Connection establishment timed out without establishing a
          connection.

    @{b}[ECONNREFUSED]@{ub}
          The attempt to connect was forcefully rejected.

    @{b}[ENETUNREACH]@{ub}
          The network isn't reachable from this host.

    @{b}[EADDRINUSE]@{ub}
          The address is already in use.

    @{b}[EINPROGRESS]@{ub}
          The socket is non-blocking and the connection cannot be
          completed immediately.  It is possible to @{"select()" Link
"select()"} for
          completion by selecting the socket for writing.

    @{b}[EALREADY]@{ub}
          The socket is non-blocking and a previous connection attempt
          has not yet been completed.

  But that still wouldn't give an accurate enough reason why you
couldn't connect- you could always check for the Miami arexx port- if
it was there, you could give the user an accurate reason for the
connect failure. =


>> The only way is to carry out as many checks as possible and
>>  hope that nothing fools the routine.
> =

> Why ? All you have to do is test to see if you can conect to the site
> in question. If you can't connect, you can't connect, (the actual
> reason is trivial, and not going to change anything) whether the user
> is online or offline is rather irrelevent. Because a user is online,
it
> doesn't automatically assume that he can connect to the entire
> "outside" world. =


  Well, exactly, all my program is interested in, is if it can connect
or not- if it can't connect it can't get/give the data it wants- end of
story! All Net programs operate like this.

> And just for the record, from looking at the name of Paul's routine
> (ConnectTCP{} for all you slow readers :o>) I would assume it tries to
> connect to something using the TCP. Offcourse I'm not the official on
> Network stuff (Paul is though :o>) so I wouldn't know. It just seems
> logical.

  Yes, Paul's routine checks to see if the bsdsocket library is online,
then if the Host exists (if crashes horribly if you try to #connect_#
to a non-existant host, from memory), then tries to #connect_# to the
host. If any of these checks fail, the Function returns a #False#.

-- =

