@NODE "Mail_512" "Re: Internet version checks"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 17 Mar 1999 03:15:53 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Internet version checks
Date: Wed, 17 Mar 1999 03:16:54 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit



>Well, I think comparing version numbers is better, since for one, not all
computers have battery backed up >clocks, (And maany of those that do,
aren't configured properly.) two, there's the millenium "bug", and three
>downloading a version text like YAM does it, is probably the best solution
anyways...


Ok....I suppose it could do both...I personally think that a date check is
better, you do not need a clock, as you simply store the last date you
downloaded (or installed...ie, the installer updates the last update date)
the file. The millenium `bug` wouldn`t be that much of a problem (ie, the
updater would say...hmmm last updated 1999, now it`s 1900....oh dear...we
seemed to have time traveled...or maybe just add 2000 to the year, if it was
less than the year of the last update), and all you`d have to do to check an
ftp file is do a list on a file, single command, where as fetching a file
would require a new port (for the data) and message overheads....and I don`t
like clogging up the internet with data that isn`t an absolute must (ie,
every user downloading the version text file every day to see if they need
an update)...the internet is slowwww now...and shabby internet programs can
only make it worse (okay...I know like..there are a tiny number of amiga
users on the internet..so it wouldn`t clog it up really...but it`s a good
principle to follow when writing internet software!)

>So, when you do eventually have a version ready that supports http and ftp
please do send it to me (If it has >Arexx, the exe will suffice, otherwise
I'll probably need the source.) Then I'll figure out a way to incorporate it
>into my installer, and the AMiGA will once and for all have a kickass
application environment that actually >works. :o>


Well, what I`ll can do the rest...but I do not have the time to create a
full blown gui for it (ie, to manage the database, options and downloads),
so I`ll just work on a cli program that does the update testing and file
fetching, and then you (or someone else) can slap a gui on the program :)


If you have any things you want in the updater...lemme know....

Dave

P.s. It`ll take me a while...as I`m working on 3 projects at the moment,
least of all a mario kart alike internet game (for the amiga!!) !!!!





@ENDNODE
