Just thinking about it actually, getting the date of an FTP'd file would
probably cause a lot more congestion than for a HTTP'd file. For example,
this is the log from when I log onto my local FTP server:

(Makes connection to 127.0.0.1)
220-    ______ __               __  __        __
220-   /_  __// /              / / / /       / /
220-    / /  / /___ ______    / /_/ /__  __ / /___
220-   / /  / __  // ____/   / __  // / / // __  /
220-  / /  / / / // __/_    / / / // /_/ // /_/ /
220- /_/  /_/ /_//_____/   /_/ /_//_____//_____/
220-                                         
220-Welcome localhost to the Pagan Software, FTP Site.
220-You are currently user number 0 out of 8.
220-
220-Server Info: Amiga A1240 32Mb RAM, 2 CD-ROMs, 3 HDDs, 33.6 Modem.
220-Local Time: Fri Mar 19 11:14:10 1999
220-URL: www.thehub.u-net.com
220-
220-Problems should be reported to rick@thehub.u-net.com.
220-
220 localhost FTP server (Amiga wu-ftpd 37.21) ready.
331 Password required for anon.
(Sends password)
230 User anon logged in.
250 CWD command successful
257 "/" is current directory.
(Sends request for directory listing)
200 PORT command successful.
200 Type set to A.
150 Opening ASCII mode data connection for AmiTCP:bin/ls -lgA .
(Program opens another connection to collect the directory listing)
226 Transfer complete.

Now in my opinion, that, plus two seperate connections is going to cause a
lot more traffic than a 1-3 line file plus a 5-6 line HTTP header.  And
that's only my wee server, think about the likes of the header that aminet
has? Plus changing through the subdirectories til you get to your one.

