That`s all very well :)...but I think your missing my key arugument...why do
ALL the web browsers have a cache?? is it

A) Because the programers got bored..and couldn`t think of any other
features to add
B) Because it serves a useful purpose by checking the LAST-MODIFIED date of
the file, and checking to see if we have already downloaded it...therefore
saving time and bandwidth by not re-downloading it (no matter how small it
is!)

Personally, I think it`s B...and I figure that getting the date, is better
than getting the file..no matter FTP or HTTP, I imagine that microsoft did a
huge resource wasting study on this when designing IE, and came out with the
same conclusion I made at the start of this disscussion :). Surely if I used
the command `HEAD` which will supply me with the LAST-MODIFIED...that will
be shorter (and use less bandwidth) than doing a GET no matter of the
attached file size. Not that it makes any difference in the whole world
(although that`s what most of my pc software seems to do...just tells me
when an update is available and downloads it, wether I want it or
not...thanks AOL!)....the best solution in my opinion would be to have a
server just designed for checking for updates...so you would say download a
text file from the `updater` server, and then the program could check
through it for software updates and fetch them...better than
connecting/disconnecting to 100 different ftp or http servers, and
downloading small files


Paranoid...who?? ME?????,

Dave....



