That is exactly what I am doing in my own program, except the text file is
stored on my own HTTP server.  You could use "HEAD", but if the updater is
built into your application then there isn't much point for the sake of a
one-three line file.  Plus all servers are different, some HTTP 1.0 servers
don't give out any headers, some do.

Plus, if the file is a single line, you're gonna end up downloading twice
that if the file has been updated.  Anyway, the original argument was
whether FTP or HTTP was better for this kind of program.  Noone, at any
point, mentioned "web browser caches" until this email from you.

Oh, and the cache's on web-browsers don't always work.  in my experience, IE
will quite happily load a web-page out of the cache even if the web-site
version has been updated.  And that usually causes no end of annoyance
cause it means having to sit and repeatidly hit the "Refresh" button until
the stupid Microsloth product gets the general idea.  

-- 
