@NODE "Mail_560" "Re: Hacker trouble"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 21:56:44 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 01 Mar 1999 15:22:43 -0500
Subject: Re: Hacker trouble

Hi Gareth

On 01-Mar-99, Gareth Griffiths wrote:
> Hi,   
>   Is it possible to 'hack' into a program executable and change data in
> it. I want to make a Registration Code Generator for NetDOCK-2 and I
don't
> want to re-compile the src. every time someone registers.

Yes, it is possible.  But not really "hacking" if it's your own program, is
it?
> 
> Is it possible to do something similar to NewZAP and move to a specified
> location in the executable, and then print data to it.

> i.e. part of an executable looks like this say:
> 
> <- the hex part in NewZAP ->  < ASC Part >
> 0000 2748 0019 2749 0020 2750 BLAHBLAHBLAH
> 
> is it possible to change it to something else via a blitz prog?

One of many possible ways:

} Allocate some memory, the size of the file.
} Load in the file, using ReadMem command
} Poke in the new values where you want them
} Save file back to disk using WriteMem
> 
> Also, I can save out data to files (like the ND-2 settings) and they are
in
> normal ASCII format. Is it possible to save them out so that they appear
in
> HEX mode when viewed with DOPUS' SmartRead command?

I don't have Dopus, so maybe I don't quite understand the question.  But if
you want to save out, for example, a word to a file as 2 bytes, use the
Mki$ command, and read it back with Cvi command.  Mkl$ does the same for
longs, or Mkq$ for quicks.  For single bytes:
a.b=(whatever)
print chr$(a) will do it.

Or, you could do like this:

(file 0 is opened for writing already)

b.b=152
w.w=5018
l.l=189754

WriteMem 0,&b,1
WriteMem 0,&w,2
WriteMem 0,&l,4

etc...


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
