@NODE "Mail_603" "Re: GTListViews"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 30 Mar 1999 19:53:29 +0100
From: "Scott" <scott@assembler.free-online.co.uk>
Subject: Re: GTListViews
Date: Tue, 30 Mar 1999 19:51:33 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 8bit

On the 29th March 1999, Mikkel L°kke made the following inaccurate statement...

>> I'm sorry I have to contradict you, Ashley, but I know with certainty
>> that ListViews are OS2 >too. I've got the 'AMIGA ROM Kernel Reference
>> Manual' V36/37 (it was written when OS3 >was not even born) and it
>> talks about ListViews. Just some tags are OS3+ only, but
>> 'GTLV_ShowSelected' and 'GTLV_Selected' do are OS2. Moreover
>> I coded other tools with ListViews without 'GTLV_ShowSelected' and
>> 'GTLV_Selected' and they perfectly work on A600-V37.

> Yes, but like it said (with big childish letters) in the AutoDocs if you use
> GTLV_ShowSelected (Or whatever) using OS2 YOU HAVE TO GIVE IT
> A POINTER TO A GTSTRING TYPE GADGET ! Do that and it works, (I
> think there is even an example of it in the manual) I know I used to have an A600.

This is wrong. The AutoDocs actually say this:

GTLV_ShowSelected (struct Gadget *) - NULL to have the currently
selected item displayed beneath the listview, or pointer to an already-
created GadTools STRING_KIND gadget to have an editable display
of the currently selected item.

Interestingly enough, this is exactly how it works. You do not have to supply
a pointer to a string gadget, just supply null and a text gadget is automatically
added to the bottom of your listview. However, the problem of Luca's code
crashing was nothing to do with this, but trying to set attributes of a gadget
that as far as the OS was concerned, didn't exist yet. As I have already pointed
out, if you move the GTSetAttrs command to after the AttachGTList command,
then all is well. I don't know, of the 20 messages you sent to the list today, the
only ones actually about programming are incorrect. It would appear that your
"Programming" isn't much better than your "Public Relations".

>> Really isn't there anyone who can test (and maybe compile) my code on
>> an A600? I've attached it again just in case.

> No. I don't think anyone who takes themselves seriously would have an A600.
> (I swapped mine for a copy of settlers)

This is exactly the sort of remark I have come to expect from someone who is
prepared to spend loads of money on a Super-Duper PC, but won't spend 50
quid on a scandoubler for his VGA monitor, just so he can moan about Blitz-Mode
displays.



Regards,
Scott

scott@assembler.free-online.co.uk



Damn the prime directive, give the Borg Windows 3.1   -   Lt. Worf



