@NODE "Mail_605" "Re: GTListViews"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 31 Mar 1999 17:51:09 +0100
Date: Wed, 31 Mar 1999 17:53:46 +0100
From: BaH <brucey@thenet.co.uk>
Subject: Re: GTListViews


My program has THREE GTStrings working off my GTListView, though I do cheat
a bit, in that I use the Value of the EventCode returned by clicking on the
list to point to an array where I get the information to fill in the 3
GTStrings.
So, in reality they aren't really attached to the ListView, but it works
the same nevertheless, and also provides more flexibilty.  The only
drawback in using this method is the extra memory for an array, on top of
the list array that is the GTListView.


Here's a quick bit of code (by no means complete, and by no means the
identical method that I'm actually using) :

GTListView 0,1,10,26,90,84,"My List",$8,mylist.listview(),0,0
GTString 0,2,10,122,79,12,"Text1",$1,20,""
GTString 0,3,10,135,79,12,"Text1",$1,20,""
GTString 0,4,10,148,30,12,"Text1",$1,3,""

AttachGTList 0,0


Repeat
  ev.l = WaitEvent
  If ev=$40 AND EventWindow=0
    Value = EventCode
    Select GadgetHit
      Case 1
        Gosub listclicked
    End Select
  EndIf
Until ev=$200

End
.listclicked
   GTSetString 0,2,MyArray(Value,1)
   GTSetString 0,3,MyArray(Value,2)
   GTSetString 0,4,MyArray(Value,3)
Return


...or something like that.

          ( BaH )
         O
        o         PowerMac 6500/250 64mb 10gigHD ZIP100 Jaz2
 ____^_o          Amiga 1260T/50 18mb 4.65gigHD's ZIP100 CD
(    )o\
(____)            brucey@thenet.co.uk
/\ /\
The Sheep has Spoken



