> you dont really need lookup tables to do rotation. a realtime rotation
> would be the same quality as you could do in most graphics software.
> the only benefit of prerendering is that if you were making the cars
> in a raytracer you could render at a particular angle to get better
> antialiasing and so on. There certainly aint no point in
> texturemapping the cars if you only ever see them from the same
> position.

But a plain rotation will see the original picture as a flat image- the
computer doesn't know that the roof off the car is higher up, then the
window's slope down to the main body. You'll need a renderer for that.
Or a PSX! If DMA couldn't do it on Amiga, I'm not sure anyone else can. 

I had a go at rotating a car, and in the end I used rotation as a rough
guide, but basically drew the graphics by hand.

BTW- I'm sure you've all seen 'GTA London'? Can't wait to steal the
Austin Powers car!!!!!!!!

