Hello Paul.

On 25-Mar-99, Paul Burkey wrote:

>>> GTA has a lot of cars (thats one of it's best features) so if you hav=
e
>>> over 30 cars with at least 32 rotations you'll have almost 1000 fairl=
y
>>> large shapes. Seems like quite a waste of memory for a rather poor
>>> rotation effect. I think the rotation will have to be real-time. The
>>> GTA engine is half-decent because it had lots of cars with very smoot=
h
>>> rotation. Cut down on either of those features and you`ve lost the
>>> point!

>> First of all GTA doesn't have LOTS of cars

> I'd say 30+ cars is lots. It depends on your definition of lots :)
> 30 cars pre-rendered in 32 angles (in various states of damage)
> gives you a few thousand images. That's what I call lots.

Yeah, and ? For one, the original GTA only had three states of damage: in=
tact, thrashed and burning wreck. You could instead just blit some damage=
s onto the car, not a big deal if you're working in chunky, you could als=
o damage the part that you actually thrash, instead of just the entire ca=
r. And I'm not saying it isn't going to take "lots" of memory, you can't =
make an omlet without breaking eggs.

>> second, on the AMiGA the shapes are probably not going to be that
>> large (Since most people aren't going to be running it in
>> 800x600x16, but more likely 320x200x8).

> Okay so if the cars are to look any good they'll have to fall into
> the 48x48 size. Lets imagine 3000 shapes at that size and you've
> got almost 7Meg in chunky mode and over 4Meg in crappy 32 colour
> planar mode. Now that's with only 30 cars and only 32 rotations
> and only 48x48. So a fairly limited/boring feature using lots of
> memory.

Well IMHO 32x32 would be best, as an 48x48 block might not give you adequ=
te space to manouver in (going 100 mph). Anyway I don't think it's a "lim=
ited/boring" effect, you said it yourself, it was what made GTA so good i=
n the first place, "lots" of cars, and smooth rotation. :o>

>> Also, GTA doesn't use realtime rotation, it also uses
>> pre-rendered shapes.

> Perhaps it does on the PC version but it would also require huge
> amounts of memory. Nothing like the 8meg limitation that Gareth
> has. The PlayStation version only uses a few meg of ram. That's
> the kind of limitation Gareth is talking about and that's why the
> PSX version does use real-time rotations.

Well the PSX also has a fair bit of hardware that can do this kind of thi=
ng. Maybe Gareth should make it CD32 only ? :o>

>> Besides, I thought the point of GTA was killing carnagae, and
>> getting away with it. Not smooth rotatioon.

> You mention only 10% of the gameplay here. It's a good job GTA
> was more interesting than this. I think people like to play with
> the different cars and cause lots of damage. It would be boring
> if the city only had a few different cars and the pre rendered
> shapes didn't show any damage. I wouldn't be the same if there
> were no school buses, fire engines, ambulances, big lorries etc.
> It's fun because you can do anything you like and it has many of
> the elements of a real city.

Well IMHO GTA isn't very interesting at all, I don't know anyone that sti=
ll plays it. (Lord knows I don't). Because the scope of the game is just =
too limited. Once you've played the first level a few times (Which you'll=
 have to, just to get past it since you need 1 mill. points to complete i=
t) You then move on to the next level, which is a different map, but othe=
rwise the same (Same shit, different day [Well except for the tank]). My =
point is that the gameplay is varied enough, and before long you'll have =
done everything, and it just gets tedious. I've played it lots, And I've =
only gotten to level 3. Not much progression IMHO.


Regards
