@NODE "Mail_701" "Re: Grand Theft AMiGA"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 27 Mar 1999 11:25:38 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 27 Mar 99 11:25:14 +0000
Subject: Re: Grand Theft AMiGA
Encoding: 7bit

Mikkel,

> > Precicely my point, using a lookup table for rotation will slow it
> > down.
> 
> Since when has realtime calculations been faster than lookup tables?

Well it depends on the situation. In Mildred's remap blits for example
it is necessary to have lookup tables because finding the closest
matching colours from the palette is such a time consuming process.
There is it logical. But with many things it is faster to do realtime
processing than to use lookup tables, and the case becomes moreso on
higher processors. If you had lookup tables for rotation you would
have to have a lot more memory access, and I have found that it is
mainly the volume of memory access and not so much the number of
instructions that slows down a routine. With rotation, well, maybe
lookup tables would be interesting, but then you're confined to the
precision with which you generate them.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk


