@NODE "Mail_740" "Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 23 Mar 1999 13:18:26 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 23 Mar 1999 06:43:31 -0500
Subject: Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)

Hi stocksjames

On 23-Mar-99, stocksjames wrote:
> Curt Esser wrote:

>> Anyway, I tried it here. Works fine, but only if I use degrader to put my
>> system into PAL - in NTSC, all the garphics are messed up.
>> 
>> Maybe you should throw a ForcePal in at the beginning, to avoid this.
> 
> I've never heard of this? Can you explain?

Well, just stick the command:

ForcePAL 

at the beginning of the program.  This makes sure the system is in PAL mode
before running the program.  Very old NTSC systems can't be forced into
PAL, and I don't think it will work if somebody is using a TV as a monitor
either, but at least this will make it work on most NTSC systems.

I don't think it causes a problem if the system is already in PAL.  But I
can't check that, so if it does try:

If NTSC        ;checks for a NTSC system
  ForcePAL
EndIf

> I suppose the music was messed up as well?

Not really, although it does play a bit faster in NTSC.
But ForcePAL will correct this also.

The only drawback is that ForcePAL causes an Enforcer hit  (not raelly
harmful, it's a "Read" from somewhere it shouldn't be reading).

There is an OS way to do this, but I don't remember it now...


> You wrote that 'Dungeon' game? That was quite good, and the source code
> was extremely useful! 

I'm glad you found it useful.  It was actually the first program I ever
wrote in Blitz  (I should say the first "Usable" program, after the normal
open-a-window-that-says-"I am a window" trash)

Of course, I later found out a lot of it could have been done much better,
but it was all done before I discovered the Blitz list...

BTW, I must admit that the reason it was all done in Amiga mode was not some
great master plan to make it usable on GFX cards in the future - I just
couldn't figure out how to use Blitz mode  :) 

> You went a bit mental with those samples,
> though...

Yes, I was having fun learning how to get the audio commands working  ;)

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




