Curt Esser wrote:

> Well, in theory NOTHING should ever cause an enforcer hit.  But I've never
> found a "read" hit to cause any real problems  (assuming the program in
> question doesn't crash at that point!)  It's just "looking" at an area of
> memory that the program doesn't own.
>
> The "write" hits are what cause the real problems.

I might be wrong here but I think that some addresses react to a read, ie if
you read
from the address for the power led then it returns the current status AND
toggles it,
so even just reading can cause problems.

    Thom



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_750" "Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 25 Mar 1999 19:05:08 +0000
From: "David McMinn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 25 Mar 1999 19:03:10 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)

> To the best of my knowledge, you get a read hit whenever your program
> tries to read something from memory that is either address 0 or belongs =
> another program, and that can cause corruption of data in your own
> program.
>  Write hits are similar except it's making an attempt to alter the memor=
y
> belonging to another program, system or address 0.

 Its not just address 0, there are a few low addresses that you should not=
 touch.

> Erm, are you sure? Reading a bit/word/long/whatever should never cause
> anything to be toggled...that's what the writes are for.  Oh, and I know
> for a fact the power led doesn't get toggled when you read it :)

 Reads could toggle stuff, 68HC11 & 12, both toggle things when you read f=
rom 
certain IO registers. Whether it happens on Amiga is different story.


