@NODE "Mail_756" "Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 25 Mar 1999 18:50:10 +0000
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Mar 1999 15:31:34 +0000
Organization: Pagan Software
Subject: Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)

I watched as Thomas Cobb hammered "Re: ForcePal (Re: My Stupid Game!)" out
on their keyboard...

>> The "write" hits are what cause the real problems.

To the best of my knowledge, you get a read hit whenever your program tries
to read something from memory that is either address 0 or belongs to
another program, and that can cause corruption of data in your own program.
 Write hits are similar except it's making an attempt to alter the memory
belonging to another program, system or address 0.

> I might be wrong here but I think that some addresses react to a read, ie
> if you read
> from the address for the power led then it returns the current status AND
> toggles it,
> so even just reading can cause problems.

Erm, are you sure? Reading a bit/word/long/whatever should never cause
anything to be toggled...that's what the writes are for.  Oh, and I know
for a fact the power led doesn't get toggled when you read it :)

