Hi stocksjames

On 25-Mar-99, stocksjames wrote:
> David McMinn wrote:
> 
>> He he he, famous last words. Enforcer is a program which makes your MMU
>> check for memory accesses where there shouldn't be any. An Enforcer hit
>> is a bad thing, there is only one program in existance which is allowed
>> to cause them (the Enforcer test program :).
> 
> Right.. ...erm.. ..what's MMU?

It's a Memory Management Unit.  Correct me if I'm wrong, but I think you
have one if you've got an 030 or better, and don't have one with 020 or
000.

It, ahhh..  Manages your Memory, I suppose?  (OK, I have no idea...)

I think it allows you to have soft-kicked "ROMS" and stuff like that...

You can check with SysInfo to make sure if you've got one or not.

I do know that Enforcer must have one to be able to run.

> Where is the enforcer test program?

It comes with the Enforcer archive.  It's just a program that purposely
cause some Enforcer hits, to be sure that Enforcer is actually working...

