@NODE "Mail_770" "Re: floats"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 26 Mar 1999 11:33:32 +0000
Sender: tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk
Date: Fri, 26 Mar 1999 11:27:38 +0000
From: Thomas Cobb <tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk>
Subject: Re: floats
Encoding: 7bit

Paul wrote:

> hiya.
>
> I need to do some conversions of .quick values into .float values,
> eventually in asm.

The IEEE standard is well documented - you should be able to find a book
which tells you haw they are represented in memory.
If you're too lazy try
http://www-dse.doc.ic.ac.uk/~nd/architecture/1718/sld001.htm but you
might not be able to get at it (I can't remember whether it is protected
for students only)  I can summarise it here:

Single precision (32 bit):

1 bit sign
8 bit exponent
23 bits significand

Double precision (64 bit):

1 bit sign
11 bit exponent
52 bit significand

The sign is 1 if negative, 0 if positive.

The exponent is in Bias-n format.  This means that %00000000 is -127,
%00000001 is -126, ..., 11111111 is 128. for single precision.
For double precision the exponent ranges from -1023 to 1024

The number is normalised.  This means that in binary the significand is
in the range 1.000000... < x < 2.0000....
(to read decimals in binary label the columns half, quarter, and eigth,
etc... so 1.101 is 1 + 1/2 + 1/8 = 1.625)
As the number is normalised the first bit is always 1 so it is left out
of the significand.

Example:
1.5 in single precision is:

0 positive number
01111111 for an exponent of nought
10000000000000000000000 to give you the half - the 1 is assumed as it is
a normalised number.

so 1.5 in decimal (1.1 x 2^0 in binary) is
%00111111110000000000000000000000 in IEEE single precision.

Easy huh?

However there are some special cases...
As our architecture lecturer put it "to please mathemeticians" - because
things like 0 (which can't be represented by normalised numbers) are
obviously not needed in the real world 8) )

If the exponent and significand bits are all zero then it gives +-0
(depending on th sign bit)
If the exponent is zero and the significand is nonzero the you get a
denormalised (not normalised) number.
If the exponent is non zero and the significand is non zero you get a
normalised number (as explained above - this is the usual case)
If the exponent is its highest value (255 for single precision) and the
significand is zero you get Infinity
If the exponent is its highest value (255 for single precision) and the
significand is non zero you get NAN (Not a number - for things like 5 /
0)

Hope this helps (don't kill me if its wrong...)

    Thom


