Subject: Re: Crack MeeeeEEEEEEEEEeeEe (KeyFile System) :)
Date: Thu, 4 Mar 1999 07:19:45 -0000
	boundary="----=_NextPart_000_000E_01BE660F.625A9A00"

This is a multi-part message in MIME format.

------=_NextPart_000_000E_01BE660F.625A9A00
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Loki,

Hmmm...took me about 1 hour to work out what it was doing (I`ve not picked
up my email for a week...honest!).....and i was probably helped by the fact
that I`ve reverse enginered many of my own blitz programs. Just a few
ideas......don`t use blitz strings...blitz does awful things with
strings..copying them to and from it`s temporary buffer...which gives
debuggers a great view of before and after strings.....try and split up your
routines...and make them less obvious (ie...don`t check everything at
once...)...maybe have a main check, just to make sure they have a loki key
file, and then somewhere later in the program check parts of the key (after
waiting a certain amount of time) and print a rude message and
exit..........I`ve done similar in many of my little programs...(nothing
dangerous...I`d never mess with their hd or internet info as theres always a
chance of your program reading in a damaged file for the key). I`m always
intrested in protecting software, and how to...I`ve been looking into the pc
side of things....and it`s pretty interesting....but nothing amazing....90%
of the time, the big companies don`t bother, or mess it up, and have to
release a patch to remove it one week later so people with funny setups can
play it....but as you say....one weeks worth of sales on the pc can`t be bad
at all ;)...........


Sleep well...

Dave

P.s. Email me if you want a few sneaky ways to increase the protection ;)
(cos I can`t give all my secrets away for every tom dick and harry to
read.......especially when tom, dick or harry might be trying to steal my
software someday!)......



