>Hello Dave
>     Hiya, Dave... ,on 04-Mar-99 you mailed me about: Re: Crack
MeeeeEEEEEEEEEeeEe (KeyFile >System) :)! So I`ma reply`in...

>Can`t say I`m not disapointed! But I`m glad you took the time out to crack
>it,.. and I`m also glad it took YOU an hour.. That`s an hour of your life
>wasted, when you would be able to grab a regged keyfile for my program
>off me for free :) As it`s going to be mailware :)
>It has served it`s purpose! :) (In this case at least :) )


LOL...YOU MEAN I SPENT 1 HOUR CRACKING IT FOR
NOTHING....AGGHGHGHGHHGH.....heheh, nah just jokeing....I love messing about
with stuff like that.....and I think it`s wise to put some protection in
atleast....

>[=> and i was probably helped by
>[=> the fact that I`ve reverse enginered many of my own blitz programs.
Just
>[=> a few ideas......

>Oh right,.. well, I wouldn`t have a clue where to start,.. Can I ask,..
>Do you think this system is good enough protection from the *average* amiga
>user?


Yeah...I doubt many people know how to use monam...or ira...and blitz basic
is pretty horrible to debug, if you`ve never done it before (well...it`s
awful even if you have). It wouldn`t take long for a cracked key to appear
though..if it`s a popular piece of software...or your asking more than the
price of a stamp for it (well...ok...maybe 99ukpence....I`m sure not all
amiga owners are that tight fisted!). The main problem is the
internet...everyone on their would be able to get a key file pretty
soon....so my advice is making it something they can`t live without...and
make sure there`s a message saying something like...for every pirated copy
of this software....theres one less chance of a future update (or one less
chance of the amiga staying alive!).....

>[=> don`t use blitz strings...blitz does awful things with
>[=> strings..copying them to and from it`s temporary buffer...which gives
>[=> debuggers a great view of before and after strings.....try and split up
>[=> your routines...and make them less obvious (ie...don`t check everything

>Erm,.. Are you talking #String$# (As you say in the keyfile message),
>cos I`ve never used that command,.. or are you just talking blitz strings?
>(as in .s variables) ???


The variables I`m afraid....lots of nasty things for strings in
blitz....lemme run down what kinda things go on when you use
strings....blitz has a temporary buffer....which it uses for string
manipulation....

say you do instr (a horrible bit of code!)

it copies the whole string to it`s buffer...the precedes to copy single
characters from the buffer to the start of the buffer (ie on top of it) and
then copies the character your looking for to the 2nd position in the
buffer, and then writes a 0 after that, then it does a subratction (or
something like that..I forget) and test for zero...and then copies the whole
string back to the buffer again.....and on and on until it finds the char
it`s looking for. And what`s worse...is that the way it copies it is by
byte?? by having 8 move.b (a1)+,(a3)+ hardcoded in a loop
(ever hear of move.w or move.l??)...anyway...that`s blitz...but what it
means is that you end up with before, during and after versions of your
strings...so when someone is watching your code they can see the strings
change, and have the original, and have the new string so they don`t have to
work stuff out for themselves...just sit back and point monam at the correct
address...(which is easy to find...the temporary buffer I mean...it usually
appears in a3 when blitz has to handle a temporary string or filename etc).

>[=> at once...)...maybe have a main check, just to make sure they have a
loki
>[=> key file, and then somewhere later in the program check parts of the
key
>[=> (after waiting a certain amount of time) and print a rude message and
>[=> exit..........I`ve done similar in many of my little
programs...(nothing

>Well there wasn`t REALLLY a lot of space for that in the keyfile analyser,
>cos it only has one purpose, but certainly in the final release things will
>be spread out a bit :)


true...it`s a lot easy to find when it happens all in a row :)

>[=> dangerous...I`d never mess with their hd or internet info as theres
>[=> always a chance of your program reading in a damaged file for the key).

>Yup, we got onto that subject ages ago if I remember rightly,.. that
>sort of coding is dodgy!


too right....especially these days....I just love how microsoft built in
their so called registery update service in windows 98 (which sends them
your system registery and tells them what software you have, and lots of
other important stuff...like info kept by your internet software!)

Dave

P.s. I hope it helps you get to get more registered users :)




