@NODE "Mail_889" "Re: Cool effects"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 6 Mar 1999 16:27:27 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 6 Mar 1999 16:26:43 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 6 Mar 99 16:26:27 +0000
Subject: Re: Cool effects
Encoding: 7bit

> Ok so If I wanted to have a part which is 'lit up', I would have to first
> make a set of colours brighter than the originals, and re-map that part to
> the lighter colours? So does the Lookup table point to the other set of
> colours? 
> 
> As you may have guessed I'm pretty new to blitz (and programming for that
> matter). Sorry if I've been repeating questions asked a million times :) 

Using MSimpleReMapMode, you would need to make a one-dimensional
table. That is, it should contain one entry for each colour in the
palette. So 256 bytes. Each byte holds the value that that particular
colour will be changed to. You could create some specific colours
lighter in your palette to help with the remapping quality and if you
know what colour to use to represent a change in intensity for each
colour you can make the lookup table easier. Otherwise you'd use a
routine to work out in 24-bit what the modified colour would ideally
be, and then search for the closest match from your palette. Note that
you need to store your table in an MTable object in order for the
blits to have access to it.

To expand on the idea, if you wanted to have multiple levels of
transparency you would need to add more dimensions to the table. Note
that normally you'd need 256x256 entries... one representing the
source colour and one representing the destination colour. But if you
have less colours in the source you can cut down the table size, so
long as you use colours justified towards the low end of the palette.
Ie, if you used just 16 intensities of brightness, in which colours 0
to 15 in the source shape represented a different brightness, then
you'd only need a 256x16 lookup table. I've coded it so that the
source shape can work in this way for less colours if needed.

So wether you draw a flat `shape' and use MSimpleReMapMode or draw a
shape with different intensities and use is up to you for the effect
that you want. It /would/ help to design your palette to aid in the
quality of the remapping, as if the ideal colour is nowhere near
anything in the palette it's going to look shite. If you had a palette
of green colours and you wanted to have a red-tinted light, it just
plain ain't going to end up that way.

MReMapMode
-- 
Paul.

