@NODE "Mail_898" "Chew on this  #:-]"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 10 Mar 1999 22:33:29 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 10 Mar 1999 22:26:26 +0000
From: david white <david@tara-1.demon.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 22:10:16 +0000
Subject: Chew on this  #:-]
Encoding: 8bit

Hi,

Ok so I see loads of people are starting to using Amiga mode as opposed to
Blitz mode for games. This is excellent, especially if you've got a graphics
card. There's also a lot of talk against Blitz mode and that you should
avoid it. There's just some things I've got to have a moan about here if you
don't mind | |\ :)))))

Amiga mode programming is REALLY HARD compared to Blitzmode (which was meant
for games).  Blitz Basic is supposed to be an easy language to learn and
use, (*Beginners* Allpurpose Symbolic Instruction Code unless I'm mistaken)
 but when it gets to OS Friendly games, you spend so much time worrying about stuff
not related to your game's engine at all, that it just drains creativity.
Not to mention performance.  Which defeats the purpose of using Blitz Basic.

How many GAMERS have a graphics card? When I say gamers I
don't mean puffa jacket N64 Boyz, but  Amiga users that just like to
have a general muck around, surf the internet, write tunes, stuff like that.
(the majority?) These are the people most likely to look at your games.
Most of these people still have a pretty average machine (030/040 and about
8MB). Loads of people still use TVs. Not by choice,  because do you know how much
a graphics card costs? If you're a student (like me)or other mere mortals,
that's A LOT! And if you have a 1200 it's not a simple case of ramming a
board up it's ass. You need a tower case, zorro slots, OS3.1 and a SVGA monitor.
ŻKer-Ching!!Ż    Before you know it you've blown Ż600 just for some extra
screenmodes.  It took me AGES to beg and steal Ż100 for a 1 gig hard drive. God
knows what I'm gonna do when that breaks down!

I am NOT knocking Amiga mode (I hope!). If you CAN do it then you SHOULD!
It's better than Blitz mode for countless reasons, eg. Forwards
compatibilty, and that Graphics cards can massivey increase performance of
Amiga-mode games.  

But the point of this moan is that I think people should be more open minded 
about Blitzmode,  after all 15khz is the Amiga native screenmode 
(eg start-up, boot options) and if you can't view it then it's not the programmers
 fault. And you've got to accept that some of us find it hard enough to afford a 
memory card never mind a graphics card.

Not to mention that Amiga mode gives WinUAE users more toys to play with.
GRRRR!

Byeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeee!
-- 

Regards,

Dave




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_899" "Re: Chew on this  #:-]"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 11 Mar 1999 02:40:10 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 11 Mar 1999 02:39:16 +0000
Date: Thu, 11 Mar 1999 01:40:16 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Chew on this  #:-]
Encoding: 7bit

david white wrote:

> Ok so I see loads of people are starting to using Amiga mode as opposed to
> Blitz mode for games. This is excellent, especially if you've got a graphics
> card.

Amiga Mode doesn`t automaticaly give you Graphics gard support. Amiga
mode
is a much better choice for modern Amiga games but graphics card support
is a different subject altogether.

> but when it gets to OS Friendly games, you spend so much time worrying
> about stuff not related to your game's engine at all, that it just
> drains creativity. Not to mention performance. Which defeats the purpose
> of using Blitz Basic.

There is no real performance loss in Amiga mode and as far as I'm
concerned Blitz mode is much harder to use. I never did work out
what the hell slices were and when a blitz beginer is faced with all
those FetchModes and that InitCopList mumbo-jumbo, it's almost time
to give up. Amiga Mode is different, open a screen (simple enough
compared to CopLists) then create a bitmap or two. Then I draw to the
bitmap and use ShowBitmap to display it. Amiga mode is certainly the
way for beginer blitzers.

> How many GAMERS have a graphics card?

I'd say most of them do. If you look at the best selling games of
the past year, Genetic Species, Quake, Napalm and Foundation. All these
are targeted (and optimized) for graphics card users.

It's good that people enjoy programming amiga mode games but gfx card
support has been so popular lately for a few reasons. Firstly it can
be VERY easy to support gfx cards using chunky modes (like the ones
provided by Mildred lib). Using chunky mode gives you MORE power to
be more CREATIVE. If you're thinking of developing a commercial game
then it will almost certainly have to support gfx-cards. These are
the main reasons why you'll see so much gfx-card talk. 

> But the point of this moan is that I think people should be more
> open minded about Blitzmode.

Amiga Mode has sprites and advanced (easier) copper control. Thats
about all it has going for it. I'm not going to say everyone should
support gfx-cards but you have to realise why the subject is so
important for most of us.

> Not to mention that Amiga mode gives WinUAE users more toys to play
> with. GRRRR!

WinUAE doesn`t support AGA "Amiga modes" but it is something that
will eventually come.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_900" "Re: Chew on this  #:-]"
