Hi, Paul

On 11-Mar-99, you wrote:

>
> 
> Amiga Mode doesn`t automaticaly give you Graphics gard support. Amiga
> mode
> is a much better choice for modern Amiga games but graphics card support
> is a different subject altogether.
> 

True, but Amiga mode makes GFX card support possible. I don't think it is at
all possible to use GFX cards in blitz mode? 

> There is no real performance loss in Amiga mode and as far as I'm
> concerned Blitz mode is much harder to use. I never did work out
> what the hell slices were and when a blitz beginer is faced with all
> those FetchModes and that InitCopList mumbo-jumbo, it's almost time
> to give up. Amiga Mode is different, open a screen (simple enough
> compared to CopLists) then create a bitmap or two. Then I draw to the
> bitmap and use ShowBitmap to display it. Amiga mode is certainly the
> way for beginer blitzers.

That's totally personal preference. I like Blitz mode for games. Amiga mode
is essential for Utilities obviously.  If you're programming in an
environment that you don't like though then unfortunatley there's going to
be a substantial performance loss. 


> I'd say most of them do. If you look at the best selling games of
> the past year, Genetic Species, Quake, Napalm and Foundation. All these
> are targeted (and optimized) for graphics card users.

 I think that depends on the people you know then. I know lots of Amiga
users, only one has a graphics card. But thent that's probably 'cos she's got
an A2000, so she can just shove one in her machine. Everyone else I know has
1200's, and it's just far too much hassle and expense to upgrade these to
RTG systems.

> 
> It's good that people enjoy programming amiga mode games but gfx card
> support has been so popular lately for a few reasons. Firstly it can
> be VERY easy to support gfx cards using chunky modes (like the ones
> provided by Mildred lib). Using chunky mode gives you MORE power to
> be more CREATIVE. If you're thinking of developing a commercial game
> then it will almost certainly have to support gfx-cards. These are
> the main reasons why you'll see so much gfx-card talk. 
> 

If you bring mildred into the equation then it upsets the balance
totally. I suppose you can use Mildred in any mode and it works the 
same. It'd still be a godsend! 

The thing about Amiga mode is that displays I feel can be a pain in the
 ass using the Blitter.
But I suppose if you use Mildred, you are doing all the hard work in a
chunky buffer and than just whacking it onto a bitmap, it matters less
whether you're using Copperlists or Screens. A bitmap is a bitmap, whether
in Amiga or Blitz mode, am I not right?


>> But the point of this moan is that I think people should be more
>> open minded about Blitzmode.
> 
> Amiga Mode has sprites and advanced (easier) copper control. Thats
> about all it has going for it. I'm not going to say everyone should
> support gfx-cards but you have to realise why the subject is so
> important for most of us.
> 

I totally understand that. And agree with it.   I suppose progress comes at
a price. It's just that the price I feel is far too high to be justified.
AGA is obsolete, but until Graphics cards can be used on a 1200 easily and
cheaply, or a new Amiga comes out, I'll just have to stick with AGA :( And
endure the face bending radiation from my 1084  -sigh-

> WinUAE doesn`t support AGA "Amiga modes" but it is something that
> will eventually come.

Really?  Oh well then. Better just stick to my miggy :))))) 


Cheers Paul



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_901" "Re: Chew on this  #:-]"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 11 Mar 1999 23:02:32 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 11 Mar 1999 23:01:30 +0000
Date: Thu, 11 Mar 1999 23:00:52 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Chew on this  #:-]
Encoding: 7bit

david white wrote:
> > Amiga Mode doesn`t automaticaly give you Graphics gard support.
> 
> True, but Amiga mode makes GFX card support possible. I don't
> think it is at all possible to use GFX cards in blitz mode?

Perhaps some kind of gfx card support could be done in Blitz mode but
thats a complicated problem. The point I wanted to make was Amiga mode
isn`t very hard to use but GFX card support can be. It depends really
on what you're doing and your target machine specs.

> But I suppose if you use Mildred, you are doing all the hard work in a
> chunky buffer and than just whacking it onto a bitmap, it matters less
> whether you're using Copperlists or Screens. A bitmap is a bitmap, whether
> in Amiga or Blitz mode, am I not right?

Sure, a Blitz bitmap is the same in any mode.

> I totally understand that. And agree with it.   I suppose progress
> comes at a price. It's just that the price I feel is far too high
> to be justified. AGA is obsolete, but until Graphics cards can be
> used on a 1200 easily and cheaply, or a new Amiga comes out, I'll
> just have to stick with AGA :( And endure the face bending radiation
> from my 1084  -sigh-

I don`t think AGA is really that bad. Modern CPU's with the latest
C2P routines can render a chunky buffer to AGA display at roughly the
same speed as a Zorro 2 based GFX card. Sure, it's never going to
give you smooth 640x512 displays but it's still fairly good with
modern games that can adapt/scale to various screen/window sizes.  I
don`t want to sound all anti-AGA or anything like that. My view is to
support AGA and GFX cards when possible and to point out that sometimes
it's not that hard to do it.

Cheers,

Pau;

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >



