@NODE "Mail_908" "Checking Shift Key"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 12 Mar 1999 16:21:02 +0000
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Fri, 12 Mar 1999 16:19:30 +0000
Date: Fri, 12 Mar 1999 16:12:16 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Checking Shift Key
Encoding: 7bit

Hi,

I cant work out the best way to check for the shift key when
a mouse button is pressed. When I get a mouse button event from
my intuition window I took a look at the Qualifier value but
the shift key didn't show up. In the end I decided to use check
for the raw key code instead which obviously works but I'm
sure there's a better way. I'm sure a lot of people use the MCP
commodity which lets you use the middle mouse button as a shift
key. It's really useful in some cases for example downloading
files using IBrowse is easy with a middle+left mouse click. So
IBrowse is able to detect the the shift key using a different
method. Perhaps this is a limitation of Blitz and there is really
a "Mouse Event Qualifier"... Perhaps I've missed something?

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_909" "Re: Checking Shift Key"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 13 Mar 1999 18:51:06 +0000
Date: Sat, 13 Mar 1999 16:26:39 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Checking Shift Key
Encoding: 7bit

Curt Esser wrote:
> > I'm sure a lot of people use the MCP
> > commodity which lets you use the middle mouse button as a shift
> > key. It's really useful in some cases for example downloading
> > files using IBrowse is easy with a middle+left mouse click. So
> > IBrowse is able to detect the the shift key using a different
> > method.
> 
> I think it's using the same method.  The difference is that Intuition
> really doesn't recognize a 3rd (middle) mousebutton.  3 button mouse
> stuff uses a patch which re-maps the middle button into something
> that Intuition does recognize

Are you sure about that? The 3rd mouse can be read without any patches
at all eg,

ev.l=Event
If ev.l=$8
  mb.w=MButtons
  If mb=0 Then NPrint "Middle Mouse Was Pressed"
  If mb=1 Then NPrint "Left Mouse Was Pressed"
  If mb=2 Then NPrint "Right Mouse Was Pressed"
  If mb=4 Then NPrint "Middle Mouse Was Released"
  If mb=5 Then NPrint "Left Mouse Was Released"
  If mb=6 Then NPrint "Right Mouse Was Released"
EndIf

This seems to show the middle mouse button works just as well as
the other buttons.

> > Perhaps this is a limitation of Blitz and there is really
> > a "Mouse Event Qualifier"... Perhaps I've missed something?
> 
> No, you didn't miss a thing.  If it's a limitation, BTW, it's
> Intuition's limitation, not Blitz (this time!)

Mathias Parnaudeau mentioned the EventQualifier command which seems
to be just what i was looking for. Thanks Mathias, I don`t know how
I missed that one!

Cheers,

Paul


-- 
