@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_910" "Re: Checking Shift Key"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 13 Mar 1999 12:53:49 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 12 Mar 1999 17:09:47 -0500
Subject: Re: Checking Shift Key

Hi Paul

On 12-Mar-99, Paul Burkey wrote:
> Hi,
> 
> I cant work out the best way to check for the shift key when
> a mouse button is pressed. When I get a mouse button event from
> my intuition window I took a look at the Qualifier value but
> the shift key didn't show up.

No, it won't show up unless a "standard" key is pressed with it.

> In the end I decided to use check
> for the raw key code instead which obviously works but I'm
> sure there's a better way.

Well, actually there isn't.  Have a look in the Intuition Autodoc under
Modify IDCMP for a complete explanation, but what you are doing seems to be
the only way to detect  keys such as Shift (by itself) that do not give an
ASCII value.

> I'm sure a lot of people use the MCP
> commodity which lets you use the middle mouse button as a shift
> key. It's really useful in some cases for example downloading
> files using IBrowse is easy with a middle+left mouse click. So
> IBrowse is able to detect the the shift key using a different
> method.

I think it's using the same method.  The difference is that Intuition
really
doesn't recognize a 3rd (middle) mousebutton.  3 button mouse stuff uses a
patch which re-maps the middle button into something that Intuition does
recognize - in this case, it "tells" Intuition that the Shift key is being
pressed when you press the middle mouse button.  Then Intuition "tells"
IBrowse that the shift key is down... 

> Perhaps this is a limitation of Blitz and there is really
> a "Mouse Event Qualifier"... Perhaps I've missed something?

No, you didn't miss a thing.  If it's a limitation, BTW, it's Intuition's
limitation, not Blitz (this time!)

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_911" "Re: Checking Shift Key"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 13 Mar 1999 23:54:22 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 13 Mar 1999 14:36:52 -0500
Subject: Re: Checking Shift Key

Hi Paul

On 13-Mar-99, Paul Burkey wrote:

> Are you sure about that? The 3rd mouse can be read without any patches
> at all eg,
> 
> ev.l=Event
> If ev.l=$8
>  mb.w=MButtons
>  If mb=0 Then NPrint "Middle Mouse Was Pressed"
>  If mb=1 Then NPrint "Left Mouse Was Pressed"
>  If mb=2 Then NPrint "Right Mouse Was Pressed"
>  If mb=4 Then NPrint "Middle Mouse Was Released"
>  If mb=5 Then NPrint "Left Mouse Was Released"
>  If mb=6 Then NPrint "Right Mouse Was Released"
> EndIf
> 
> This seems to show the middle mouse button works just as well as
> the other buttons.

Yes, I didn't know this was possible.  I suppose I ought to read my OS 3.1
manual one of these days  ;)


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
