@NODE "Mail_948" "Re: assembly question"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 18 Mar 1999 18:58:17 +0000
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Wed, 17 Mar 1999 13:47:19 +0300
Subject: Re: assembly question
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 26-Feb-99, Jake Frederick wrote.

>  My friend has another assembly question for you all:
>      Does the blitz assembler compiler handle labels in its branches?In=

other
>  words, do I have to enter the memory offset o the subroutine or can I =
gie
the
>  compiler a label an then use the assembler bcc command to jump to that=

>  label?
>  =

>    Can anyon give me some easy to follow examples of blitz compatible
assembler
>  for: For/Next type loops, gotos to a label, conditional gotos (probabl=
y
used
>  in the fornext exampl). Any help on this matter would help. I am worki=
ng
on a
>  simple 3-d object placement routine and doing most of it in assembler
would
>  be great. Also, is there anyway to use the getreg or putreg commands
INSIDE
>  an assembler block? I have not had problems using those commands insid=
e
the
>  block, but I fear a (d) or (a) register conflict (a3?)?
>  =


well here is for-next loop if the looping value is not used.

    move.w    #loopcounter,d7    ; how many times we loop
    subq.w    #1,d7        ; we need to sub one for DBRA purposes
loop    <Do loop stuff here>
    dbra    d7,loop        ; loop until couter is -1

And here is for-next loop where we use the counter and step values!

For    move.l    #initcounter,d7    ; Counter initial value
    move.l    #endcounter,d6    ; Counter end value
    move.l    #step,d5    ; step we use in the looping
    cmp.l    d7,d6        ; are we looping up or down?
    bgt    _up

_down    bsr    _loopstuff    ; execute loopstuff subroutine
    add.l    d5,d7        ; add step to loop counter
    cmp.l    d7,d6        ; test if we have looped enogh
    ble    _down        ; if not then we continue looping
    bra    Next        ; else we go to end of loop

_up    bsr    _loopstuff    ; execute loopstuff subroutine
    add.l    d5,d7        ; add step to loop counter
    cmp.l    d7,d6        ; test if we have looped enogh
    bge    _up        ; if not then we continue looping
    bra    Next        ; else we go to end of loop

_loopstuff
    <Do your stuff here>
    rts

Next                ; end of FOR-NEXT LOOP


Well there are faster ways to do the second version and there are some
usefull tricks in looping too, but I just tought the basics would be enou=
gh
now. So if you need more I could do some fast optimized loop examples.

-- =


            Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen   A1260 50MB 4.5GB 2X 56k HP LaserJet4L
            EMail: sami.naatanen@dlc.fi




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_949" "Re: assembly question"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 18 Mar 1999 21:02:01 +0000
From: Mathias PARNAUDEAU <mathias.p@wanadoo.fr>
Date: Thu, 18 Mar 1999 14:48:08 +0100
Subject: Re: assembly question
Encoding: quoted-printable

Le 26-F=E9v-99, Jake Frederick a =E9crit:

Hi Jake,

>My friend has another assembly question for you all:
>    Does the blitz assembler compiler handle labels in its branches?In o=
ther
>words, do I have to enter the memory offset o the subroutine or can I gi=
e the
>compiler a label an then use the assembler bcc command to jump to that
>label?

You can and you should labels, and I don't know how to code without label=
s !

>  Can anyon give me some easy to follow examples of blitz compatible
assembler
>for: For/Next type loops, gotos to a label, conditional gotos (probably =
used
>in the fornext exampl). Any help on this matter would help. I am working=
 on a
>simple 3-d object placement routine and doing most of it in assembler wo=
uld
>be great. Also, is there anyway to use the getreg or putreg commands INS=
IDE
>an assembler block? I have not had problems using those commands inside =
the
>block, but I fear a (d) or (a) register conflict (a3?)?

For/Next loop :

For i=3D1 to 10 : Block of instructions : Next

   move.w i,d0
   subq #1,d0                     ; d0 is a counter =3D i-1
label:
   Block of instructions
   =

   dbra d0,label

with at the end of the program :

i:
   dc.w 35                           ; 35 is an example, of course :-)


Repeat/Until loop :

Repeat : Block of instructions : Until x<>y

   move.w y,d1                        ; x and y have a value =

   ...
   move.w x,d2                        ; =

label:
   ...
   Block of instruction where the value of y (d1) change   =

   ...
   cmp d2,d1                           ; compare x and y
   bne label                            ; if not equal, go to label


It's not neccessary to move variables into registers, but it's quicker.
You can compare a variable (label) with a register : CMP i,d3 with i decl=
ared
(i: dc.w 0).

What is important is to understand how to compare values and what are the=

tests (bne, bmi, beq, ...).

>Thank you or your time.

No problem. I wish these explanations are clear enough.

Bye,

                           Mathias



@ENDNODE
