Hello Oliver.

On 08-Mar-99, Oliver Marks wrote:

> I am doing an assignment on assembler at college and was hoping some
> one would write a simple program in blitz which lets you input numbers
> and will display the lowest number entered the highest number entered
> and the mean.
> it has to be completely in assembler the only commands you are allowed
> to use are input and print.

Very easy, for the lowest number, (providing, one is in d0, and the other=
 in d1),

CMP.l    d0,d1
BLT    d0issmallest
<do d1issmallest>

And to get the highest value,

CMP.l    d0,d1
BGT    d0isbiggest
<do d1isbiggest>

Mean value ? I have no idea what that is.

> i have 9 programs to write and think i can do the rest if i have this
> one to go bye any help will be greatfully recieved.

Erm, I don't think so. Anyway, here are they, note that Intel assembly is=
 read backwards e.g.

Motorola MOVE.l #$0,d0 will move the value 0 to d0
Intel MOVE.l #$0,d0 won't even compile, since for one thing, Intel regist=
ers aren=F8t called d0, and it certainly can=F8t move the contents of a (=
non-exsisting) register to the value 0 :o>

I hope I've been some help. Incindently, if you want some help on Motorol=
a style assembly I'll be happy to help you... (Maybe you should have paid=
 more attention at class ? :o>) =



Regards
-- =

