@NODE "Mail_984" "AAARGHH! (formerly Grand Theft Amiga)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 19 Mar 1999 13:46:45 +0000
From: "C.J.R.Jarvis" <C.J.R.Jarvis@wkac.ac.uk>
Subject: AAARGHH! (formerly Grand Theft Amiga)
Date: Fri, 19 Mar 1999 13:42:09 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"

I'm sorry but any type of rotate looks totally poor. What on earth would
Stardust/SuperStardust/Super Skidmarks have looked like if they had used
rotate?!
personally, I would render the cars rotating, that way they would have a
more solid feel and not look like an amos project.
Really it's not a waste of memory. If you're talking about a lowres game,
then 1000 cars shapes isn't that much considering the size of the cars. To
be honest, anyone who would have a fast enough machine to support real time
rotation in blitz will probably have enough memory for the shapes. Obviously
you'll have to store the shapes in fast mem, but that's more than easy
enough these days.

	Chris



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_985" "Re: AAARGHH! (formerly Grand Theft Amiga)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 19 Mar 1999 17:15:10 +0000
Date: Fri, 19 Mar 1999 17:14:38 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: AAARGHH! (formerly Grand Theft Amiga)
Encoding: 7bit

"C.J.R.Jarvis" wrote:
> personally, I would render the cars rotating, that way they would have
> a more solid feel and not look like an amos project.

Pre rendered cars and real-time rotated cars is the same thing apart
from the real-time bit? I mean claiming that one looks better than the
other is mute unless you implement directional lighting (the main wow-
factor in Stardust). Even that could be done in real-time, especially
if the cars were actually 3D models rather than plain old bitmap
sprites. Perhaps it would be faster to use polygon based cars, texture
mapping and shading than it would to do bitmap rotation. It would
certainly be a good way to win some points over the dated GTA engine
but perhaps not possible to pull off given average Amiga specs.

> What on earth would Stardust/SuperStardust/Super Skidmarks have
> looked like if they had used rotate?!

Skidmarks was an isometric game and I don't think it's possible to
rotate bitmaps in isometric space. But these are good examples of
games that use very few objects that can be pre rendered in very
little memory (by today's standards).

> Really it's not a waste of memory. If you're talking about a
> lowres game, then 1000 cars shapes isn't that much considering
> the size of the cars.

1000 was just a rough guess. I didn't even consider the fact that the
cars get damaged and the damage is also rotated. So you've already
doubled the number of shapes with one single "damage spot". The cars
can be damaged in many places. Some of the vehicles are quite big, there
are buses, Ambulances, fire engines etc. Hey, why not do GTA with less
cars, remove all the typical city vehicles, no ultra smooth rotation,
no vehicle damage and so on ... Before too long you've lost all the
reasons why GTA is cool. Perhaps you'll be left with smooth scrolling
car theft with a bit of killing thrown in for fun :)

I'm trying to point out why GTA is actually impressive despite its
simplistic looks. There's a lot of subtle detail in the game and if
you loose too much of it you've lost the point. If someone is going
to make a GTA clone then it's best to think about all the possible
problems and benefits of the various methods that are available. Pre
rendered graphics, real time rotations, 3D polygon based objects and
so on. They all have big benefits and big restrictions. Is computing
power was no restriction then 3D polygons would be the best option
(imagine if the cars could roll over in a crash!) and pre rendered
sprites would be the worst (not much variation withiout massive memory
usage).

> To be honest, anyone who would have a fast enough machine to support
> real time rotation in blitz will probably have enough memory for the
> shapes.

And vice versa? :)

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >



@ENDNODE
