@NODE "Mail_992" "Re: 3 questions this time"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 19:09:53 +0000
From: "Philippe Bovier" <bovier@club-internet.fr>
Organization: NightLight Team
Date: 1 Mar 99 19:59:36 -0100
Subject: Re: 3 questions this time
Encoding: 8bit

Hello Mikkel L°kke,

> > we want to know if It's possible to create gadgets or
> > listviews directly in a screen (pubscreen) and not in a window in system mode
> > for example ???
> 
> No. At least not standard gadgets. why don't you want to use windows ?

if a program open a window and the pointer is outside of this window, this
window dissapeared because mcp, for example, show only the window when the
pointer is.

if a program use a screen, and after a window of this program is opened, this
window don't disapeared is the pointer is outside of this window.

we search:

-a small code or example to keep a window at his original position is the pointer
is outside of this window and mcp is active for example.

or:

how to put gadgets in a screen directly for keeping the program's window always
with the program. 

> > We want to program with the use of boopsi but we don't have examples to show how
> > programming Boopsi. Where can we found examples with boopsi and the library or .fd ???
> 
> .....I'm not sure Blitz is very optimal at doing OOP in the first place.

my friends want to program the gadgets in the drawer sys:classes/gadget of
the wb and want to found an fd or examples to make that.

 
> > Problem: how create and load a picture more big than the bitmap initializated in
> > the beginning with blitz system mode (ex:allocbitmap_...) ???
> 
> You can't. Obviously. If you allocate memory for a bitmap, then load in a bigger one, when the boundries of the memory is reached, you will be writing into memory you don't own, which will crash the system. What you should do is wait allocating your bitmap uuntill you know what size it is....

when we try to open a window with allocbitmap function, for example 100*100
and after load an icon 50*120 inside this window, the picture of the icon is
more big than the window.

for  example,  with the irt program of life team, (a program to manipulate
icons)  an  icon more big than the irt window have the same dimensions than
the  window of irt, the rest of the gfx of the icon doesn't appared outside
the irt window.
-- 
Philippe Bovier ( *Mrod* ) mailto:Bovier@club-internet.fr
------------>> Friend's project in Blitz Basic <<----------
- De-Archiveur1.3 -> Aminet      - FileFrog   -> In progress
- XFD GUI Package -> In progress - BUBBLE AGA -> stand by


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_993" "Re: 3 questions this time"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 1 Mar 1999 23:31:15 +0000
 (envelope-from flameduck@software.dk)
 (envelope-from flameduck@software.dk)
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Mon, 01 Mar 1999 23:55:28 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: 3 questions this time
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Philippe.

On 01-Mar-99, Philippe Bovier wrote:

>>> we want to know if It's possible to create gadgets or
>>> listviews directly in a screen (pubscreen) and not in a window in sys=
tem mode
>>> for example ???

>> No. At least not standard gadgets. why don't you want to use windows ?=


> if a program open a window and the pointer is outside of this window, t=
his
> window dissapeared because mcp, for example, show only the window when =
the
> pointer is.

What ?!? MCP doesn't make windows "disappear".

> if a program use a screen, and after a window of this program is opened=
, this
> window don't disapeared is the pointer is outside of this window.

No. Windows only disappear hen you close them, it really neat actually.

> we search:

> -a small code or example to keep a window at his original position is t=
he pointer
> is outside of this window and mcp is active for example.

Just don't allow the window to be moved. It says how to do that in the ef=
erance manual.

> or:

> how to put gadgets in a screen directly for keeping the program's windo=
w always
> with the program. =


Now you've lost me completely. I was (sorta) okay until this point. A pro=
gram's window is allways "with" the program.

>>> We want to program with the use of boopsi but we don't have examples =
to show how
>>> programming Boopsi. Where can we found examples with boopsi and the l=
ibrary or .fd ???

>> .....I'm not sure Blitz is very optimal at doing OOP in the first plac=
e.

> my friends want to program the gadgets in the drawer sys:classes/gadget=
 of
> the wb and want to found an fd or examples to make that.

I don't think there ae any... I don't know. Blitz doesn't do Object Orien=
ted Programming.

>> > Problem: how create and load a picture more big than the bitmap init=
ializated in
>> > the beginning with blitz system mode (ex:allocbitmap_...) ???

>>  You can't. Obviously. If you allocate memory for a bitmap, then load =
in a bigger one, when the boundries of the
>> memory is reached, you will be writing into memory you don't own, whic=
h will crash the system. What you should do is
>> wait allocating your  bitmap untill you know what size it is....

> when we try to open a window with allocbitmap function, for example 100=
*100
> and after load an icon 50*120 inside this window, the picture of the ic=
on is
> more big than the window.

So ?

> for  example,  with the irt program of life team, (a program to manipul=
ate
> icons)  an  icon more big than the irt window have the same dimensions =
than
> the  window of irt, the rest of the gfx of the icon doesn't appared out=
side
> the irt window.

Erm, I havn't seen IRT, but my guess is they load the icon onto a seperat=
e bitmap, and then blit that bitmap onto the window bitmap using BlitBitM=
apRastPort_ or something (like BitmapToWindow ?). That would be the sensi=
ble thing to do....


Regards
-- =

